{[%evp 0,56,30,-12,21,-15,21,23,24,3,13,-9,-9,-16,-4,-13,-15,-37,10,10,10,10,
13,3,-7,-7,9,-30,1,-1,0,-9,-13,7,-5,-38,-38,-51,-44,-43,-14,-25,26,-7,20,-11,2,
-32,-30,-65,-66,-190,-190,-280,-262,-268,-371,-29995,-29996] Dark Square
Strategy - In this lecture I will show you the ideas of the so-called dark
square strategy for Black pieces. The main rule is that when we exchange our
dark square bishop for the opponent's knight we are trying to put all our
pawns on the dark squares. We are trying to restrict the opponent's bishop.
This strategy is an excellent way to play for a win with Black because we
create an imbalance early in the game.} 1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4 4. Qc2 {
This is an interesting system, very similar to Nimzo-Indian Defence. White
delays d4 with the first to provoke Bxc3. Later he can choose between setups
with d3 or d4.} d6 $5 {This is an interesting sideline with less than 100
games in the database. I like the idea a lot and was inspired by several games
of GM Andrey Sokolov. The idea is to employ the dark square strategy - putting
all the pawns on the dark squares after the exchange on c3.} 5. a3 Bxc3 6. Qxc3
a5 {Black can choose between different setups, but this move is generally
always useful in such positions.} 7. b3 e5 {If White didn't play d4, Black
could stop it.} 8. g3 c5 {In my opinion, this is the best placement for Black
pawns. Without the knight on c3 is hard for White to take advantage of the
weakened "d5" and "b5" squares. This move also makes the advances d4 and b4
almost impossible.} 9. Bg2 Nc6 10. d3 O-O 11. O-O Bg4 {with the strategical
threat to exchange the knight and jump Nd4 next ruining White's structure.} 12.
Re1 {This is a prophylactic against Bxf3 and Nxd4 but also an eventual Bh3
with the exchange of the bishops.} Qd7 {When we are employing dark-squared
strategy is useful for us to exchange the light square bishop.} 13. Rb1 Rab8 {
This wasn't necessary, but I wanted to avoid the pin on the h1-a8 diagonal and
even to prepare the advance b5 on some occasions.} 14. Bg5 {In such a position
White's dream is to exchange his dark square bishop.} Ne8 15. Nd2 f6 16. Be3 b6
{The triumph of the dark square strategy. Now all my pawns are on dark squares
beside the one on h7.} 17. Nf1 Nc7 {Black's position is much better now. I can
choose between b5, d5, or f5 advance.} 18. Bd2 Bh3 {The light square bishop is
the only defender of White's king.} 19. Bh1 f5 {I decided to go for the most
straightforward continuation. Planning a direct attack against the king} 20. f4
exf4 21. gxf4 Rbe8 22. Ng3 Kh8 {This was a prophylactic move that wasn't
necessary.} 23. Kf2 d5 24. cxd5 Nxd5 25. Bxd5 Qxd5 {Now White's king is
desperately weak and the game ended quickly after:} 26. Rg1 Nd4 27. Be3 Bg4 28.
Bxd4 Rxe2+ {I like this game very much, because it was purely positional. I
manage to outplay very convincingly my experienced opponent without giving him
any chances. In general in my practice those type of positions appeared a lot.}
0-1

