1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d6 {Kurajca's speciality. I understood
that this move was quite interesting when I prepared against him. I like
Black's flexibility, he can choose between different setups: c5, e5, b6, etc...
} 5. Nf3 {One of the many possibilities for White.} Nbd7 6. Bd2 b6 7. e4 Bb7 8.
Bd3 {It seems that White achieves everything that he wants: healthy pawn
structure, strong center, well-developed pieces, but the things are not that
easy.} e5 9. a3 (9. d5 {was tried in a recent game, but Black is just fine
after the simple:} Nc5 10. a3 Bxc3 11. Bxc3 O-O 12. b4 $2 Nxd3+ 13. Qxd3 Nh5
$17 {0-1 (60) Luberanski,J (2274)-Rozentalis,E (2520) Warsaw 2021}) 9... Bxc3
10. Bxc3 Qe7 11. O-O O-O 12. Rfe1 Nh5 {again this idea is very strong.} 13. b4
Nf4 14. Bf1 (14. Bd2 Nxd3 15. Qxd3) 14... f5 $1 {even with an open center,
this move is very strong} 15. d5 (15. exf5 $2 Bxf3 $19) (15. dxe5 fxe4 16. exd6
Qf7) 15... fxe4 16. Qxe4 Qf7 17. Nd2 b5 $3 18. cxb5 Bxd5 19. Qe3 Nf6 20. f3 Qg6
21. Rac1 h5 22. a4 h4 23. Kh1 h3 24. gxh3 Qh5 25. Ne4 Nxh3 26. Rc2 Nf4 27. Bb2
Rf7 28. Bc4 Raf8 29. Rg1 Nxe4 30. Bxd5 Nxd5 31. Qxe4 Qxf3+ 32. Qxf3 Rxf3 33.
Bc1 R8f7 34. Bd2 e4 35. Be1 Rd3 36. Rc4 e3 37. Bh4 Rf4 38. Rxf4 Nxf4 39. Bg5
Nh3 0-1

