1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Qe8 {This is
another interesting try to reach a playable position and to use a dark-square
strategy. The idea is to avoid the pin on the h4-d8, to prepare e6-e5 and to
support b5.} 7. f3 d6 8. Bg5 Nfd7 9. e3 e5 10. d5 $2 {an instructive mistake.
The combination e3 + d5 is just not very good for White.} a5 11. b4 {Another
mistake, White is not developed, but open the queenside.} f5 12. Bh4 axb4 13.
axb4 Rxa1+ 14. Qxa1 Na6 15. Qa3 Nb6 16. c5 $2 {after this pseudo-active move,
White is just lost.} Nxd5 17. Bc4 Be6 18. cxd6 Naxb4 19. Qb3 cxd6 0-1

