1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3 6. Qxc3 b6 7. b3 Bb7 8.
Bb2 d6 9. e3 e5 10. d4 Ne4 11. Qc2 Ng5 12. Nxg5 Qxg5 13. d5 {This move closes
Black's b7-bishop, but gives Black a free hand in the center.} Nd7 14. g3 $2 (
14. Bd3 $1 {is the best and the most natural move.} Qxg2 $2 {the pawn is not
hanging.} (14... f5 15. f4 exf4 16. O-O $16) 15. Bxh7+ Kh8 16. Be4 $16) (14.
O-O-O {is another decent try, but opposite castling is always a bit risky.})
14... c6 $1 15. Bh3 (15. Bg2 cxd5 16. cxd5 (16. Rd1) 16... Rac8 17. Qe2 Qg6 {
[%cal Rc8c2]}) 15... Rad8 16. dxc6 Bxc6 17. O-O Nc5 $3 {with the idea to
occupy the weak light square like "e4" and "d3"} (17... e4 $6 18. b4 Ne5 19.
Bxe5 Qxe5 {[%cal Ra1d1,Rd1d4,Rf1d1,Rc2d2]}) (17... Qh6 18. Bg2 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 f5
20. Rad1 $11) 18. Bg2 (18. b4 Be4 19. Qd1 Nd3 $17) 18... Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Qg6 $3 {
The key idea. Usually we are not exchanging queens when we have knight against
bishop, but here is different case. Black is fighting for the important "d3"
square.} 20. Qc3 d5 21. Qxe5 dxc4 22. Rad1 Rxd1 23. Rxd1 cxb3 $19 24. Rd4 f6
25. Qd6 h6 26. e4 Re8 27. f3 Qf7 28. a4 Ne6 29. Rd5 Rc8 30. Rd2 Rd8 31. Qb4
Rxd2+ 32. Qxd2 Nc5 33. a5 Qd7 34. Qb4 Qa4 35. Qd2 Qc4 36. axb6 axb6 37. Kf2
Nd3+ 38. Ke3 Nxb2 39. Qxb2 Kf7 40. h4 Ke6 41. f4 Qc2 42. f5+ Kd6 43. Qd4+ Kc7
44. Qa4 Qc3+ 0-1

