{[%evp 0,138,23,23,38,6,-2,-3,33,-12,-2,4,9,11,3,-18,-18,-10,-10,0,-4,-17,-31,
-12,-19,-14,22,0,-5,-22,-21,-27,-11,-39,-1,-31,12,4,32,22,4,11,41,11,23,11,32,
18,29,-22,-9,-19,-36,-45,-41,-44,14,-67,-49,-44,-15,-77,-57,-64,-67,-55,-65,
-65,-50,-57,-36,-47,-48,-97,-37,-64,-64,-64,-14,-64,-42,-105,-46,-86,-74,-75,
-86,-147,-153,-141,-145,-168,-175,-172,-173,-179,-189,-194,-191,-196,-194,-203,
-190,-190,-179,-193,-192,-182,-187,-182,-172,-171,-192,-229,-319,-319,-319,
-318,-337,-364,-373,-509,-527,-527,-547,-1011,-1022,-1022,-1022,-1022,-1032,
-1032,-28793,-29965,-29966,-29967,-29968,-29969,-29970,-29977,-29974]} 1. d4
Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. Nf3 c5 6. dxc5 Na6 7. e3 Nxc5 8. Bd2 b6
9. a3 Bxc3 10. Bxc3 Bb7 11. Be2 d6 12. O-O e5 {Another type of dark square
strategy. You can easily see that all Black pawns are on the dark squares
after the swap of the bishop. Now White has healthy structure and bishop pair,
but it is not clear what his plan is. The d6-pawn is weak but can be easily
protected. The e4-square is available for Black's pieces. Also, Black has an
idea to put pressure on the c-file after Rc8 followed by b5 or d5 - break.} 13.
b3 (13. b4 Nce4 {[%cal Ra8c8,Rd8e7,Rb6b5,Rd6d5] and the c4-pawn becomes
critically weak because can't be attacked by another pawn.}) 13... Rc8 14. Rfc1
Qe7 15. b4 Nce4 16. Be1 Rc7 17. Qb2 Qe6 {The computer always prefers White in
such positions, but over the board, I would choose Black.} 18. a4 Ba6 19. b5
Bb7 20. a5 h6 21. Rd1 Rfc8 22. h3 Nd7 23. Nd2 Nec5 24. axb6 axb6 25. f3 e4 $1 {
not allowing e3-e4} 26. fxe4 Nxe4 27. Nxe4 Bxe4 28. Bg3 Qg6 29. Kh2 d5 $17 {
Karpov has an advantage and converts it later.} 30. Rac1 Nf6 31. Bf1 Rc5 32.
cxd5 Nxd5 33. Rxc5 Rxc5 34. Qd4 Kh7 35. Rd2 h5 36. Rf2 f6 37. Be2 Nc3 38. Bf1
Nd5 39. Be2 f5 40. Be5 Nc3 41. Bf1 Nxb5 42. Qb2 Nc7 43. Bxc7 Rxc7 44. g3 h4 45.
Qe5 Rc1 46. Qf4 hxg3+ 47. Qxg3 Qxg3+ 48. Kxg3 g5 49. Ba6 Rg1+ 50. Kh2 Rb1 51.
