1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d6 5. e4 c5 {This variation is similar to
the 4...b6 line} (5... e5 $6 {This move is objectively suspicios, but still
quite interesting} 6. Qa4+ {It seems that Black loses a piece, but that is not
the case here.} Nc6 7. d5 b5 $3 (7... Bxc3+ $2 8. bxc3 $18 {0-1 (27)
Rakhimzhan,A (2273)-Seul,G (2372) Chess.com INT 2020}) 8. Qxb5 (8. cxb5 Nd4 $13
) 8... Rb8 9. Qxc6+ Bd7 10. Qa6 Nxe4 $19 {[%cal Re4c3,Re4c5]}) 6. d5 (6. dxc5
dxc5 7. e5 Nfd7 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. a3 Qa5 10. Bf4 Nd4 11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. axb4 Qxa1+
13. Nd1 a5 {0-1 (30) Vedrickas,T (2395)-Stocek,J (2604) Tornelo INT 2020}) (6.
a3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Nc6 8. d5 Na5 {we are in some strange Nimzo, where Black is
doing fine.}) (6. e5 $2 cxd4 7. exf6 dxc3 8. bxc3 Qxf6 9. Ne2 Bc5 $19) 6...
exd5 7. exd5 (7. cxd5 Qe7 {[%cal Rf6d5,Rf6e4]}) 7... O-O (7... Qe7+) 8. Bd3
Nbd7 9. Nf3 Re8+ 10. Be3 b5 $1 {Typical idea in such structure.} (10... Rxe3+
$6 11. fxe3 $16) 11. O-O $6 (11. b3 $2 Ng4 $15 {[%cal Rd8f6,Re8e3]}) (11. cxb5
$5) 11... bxc4 12. Bxc4 {This structure with a weak pawn on d5 is just
favourable for Black.} Nb6 13. Bb5 Bd7 14. Bc6 Bxc6 15. dxc6 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Qc7
17. Bg5 Ne4 18. c4 Qxc6 $19 {Black finally won a pawn and has a winning
position. The rest is a matter of simple technique.} 19. a4 h6 20. Bf4 d5 21.
cxd5 Nxd5 22. Be5 Nb4 23. Qc4 Qd5 24. Rac1 Qxc4 25. Rxc4 f5 26. h3 Rad8 27. g4
Rd3 28. gxf5 Rxf3 29. Rxe4 Nd3 30. Kg2 Rxf5 31. f4 g5 32. Rf3 c4 33. Rxc4 Ne1+
0-1

