{[%evp 0,80,16,28,27,-16,-9,-9,-3,1,20,20,38,36,28,35,52,38,35,38,37,8,22,-10,
-6,-7,-4,-13,-16,-21,-3,-22,-13,-19,-41,-65,-70,-71,-56,-54,-53,-56,-60,-66,
-52,-51,-41,-43,-43,-43,59,-130,-32,-126,-141,-154,-126,-204,-150,-138,-87,
-120,-89,-81,-33,-242,-197,-312,-342,-342,-463,-471,-471,-471,-488,-486,-1111,
-1170,-1203,-1368,-1484,-1484,-998] In the first game, I would like to start
with one of the most classical games in Nimzo-Indian Defence - Johner -
Nimzowitsch. This example is a fantastic illustration of Black blockading
ideas in positions with doubled pawns.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O
({A better version of Black's idea is} 4... c5 5. Bd3 Nc6 6. Nf3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3
d6 8. e4 e5 9. d5 Ne7 10. Nh4 h6 {keeping the possibility to castle long, for
example:} 11. f3 Qa5 12. Qc2 g5 13. Nf5 Nxf5 14. exf5 Bd7 15. Be3 O-O-O 16. Kd2
$2 Rde8 17. Rae1 Ba4 $1 18. Qb1 Kc7 19. Bc2 Bxc2 20. Qxc2 Qa6 21. Qb3 Nd7 $1 {
[%cal Gd7b6]} 22. Bf2 Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 23. a4 Nb6 24. Re4 Qxa4 25. Qxa4 Nxa4
$19 {0-1 Lombard,A (2420)-Csom,I (2490)/Biel 1976/IZT (40)} 26. Ra1 $140 Nb6
27. Rxa7 Ra8 28. Rxa8 Rxa8 {[%cal Ga8a2]}) 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Bxc3 8.
bxc3 d6 {[%cal Ge6e5]} 9. Nd2 ({An alternative is} 9. e4 e5 10. d5 Ne7 11. Nh4
h6 12. g3) 9... b6 {/\10...e5 11.d5 Na5 12.Nb3 Nb7 - Nimzowitsch} ({more
logical looks the immediate} 9... e5 10. d5 Ne7 ({also possible is} 10... Na5
11. Nb3 $140 e4 12. Be2 Nd7 13. f4 exf3 14. gxf3 f5) 11. e4 h6 {planning Nh7
and f7-f5}) 10. Nb3 (10. f4 {will be met by} e5 11. fxe5 $140 dxe5 12. d5 Na5
13. Nb3 Nb7 14. e4 Ne8 {[%cal Ge8d6,Gb7d6]}) 10... e5 11. f4 $6 ({After} 11. d5
{Black replies with} e4 $1 12. dxc6 (12. Be2 Ne5) 12... exd3 13. Qxd3 Qc7 14.
e4 Qxc6 15. f3 Be6 16. Bf4 (16. Bg5 Nd7 17. Be7 Rfe8) 16... Nh5 $5 (16... Qa4
17. Nd2 Ne8 $13) 17. Bxd6 Bxc4 18. Qxc4 Qxd6 $11) ({but deserved attention} 11.
e4 $5 exd4 $140 12. cxd4 cxd4 13. Bb2) 11... e4 $1 ({This is probably stronger
than} 11... exd4 12. cxd4 cxd4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. exd4 d5 15. Ba3 Re8 16. c5 $13
) 12. Be2 Qd7 $1 {By taking control over diagonal c8-h3 Black restricts the
mobility of White's kingside pawns.} ({Worse was} 12... Ne8 {because allowed
White to close the position after} 13. g4 f5 14. d5 (14. dxc5 dxc5 15. Qd5+
Qxd5 16. cxd5 Ne7 17. Rd1 Nd6) 14... Ne7 15. g5 $11) 13. h3 $6 {This move
weakens the g3-square.} ({Also dubious looks} 13. f5 $6 Ne7 14. g4 h5 $1 15. h3
(15. g5 Nh7) 15... hxg4 16. hxg4 g6 $1) ({perhaps the best was} 13. Bd2) ({or} 
13. a4 a5 14. Bd2) 13... Ne7 14. Qe1 ({Now after} 14. Bd2 {was possible} h5 $5
{preventing g2-g4} ({less clear is} 14... Nf5 {[%cal Gf5g3]} 15. Qe1 g6 16. g4
Ng7 17. Qh4 Nfe8 18. a4 f5 19. g5 Nc7 $13) 15. Bxh5 $140 (15. Be1 Nf5 16. Bf2
g6) 15... Nxh5 16. Qxh5 Qa4 (16... Ba6 17. f5 f6 18. Rf4 Bxc4) 17. f5 f6 18.
Rf4 $2 Bxf5 $1) 14... h5 $1 {An important move in Black`s plan of blockade,
which completely restricts White`s counterplay.} 15. Bd2 ({If} 15. Qh4 $6 {
, then} Nf5 16. Qg5 $140 $2 Nh7 17. Qxh5 Ng3) 15... Qf5 $1 {Black transfers
his queen to the kingside intending to prepare later an attack against white
king.} 16. Kh2 Qh7 17. a4 Nf5 $5 {Threatening Ng4+ and at the same time
intending to occupy the g3-square by h5-h4 and Ng3.} (17... a5) 18. g3 ({
In case of} 18. a5 {Black can continue with} Ng4+ $5 (18... Be6) 19. Bxg4 (19.
hxg4 $4 hxg4+ 20. Kg1 g3 $19) 19... hxg4 20. axb6 gxh3 21. gxh3 Nh4 22. Qg3
Nf3+ 23. Kg2 (23. Rxf3 exf3 24. Qxf3 Bf5 25. bxa7 Bc2 26. Nc1 Be4 27. Qe2 Qh4 {
[%cal Gh4e7]}) 23... a5 $1 {e.g.} 24. Rfb1 Rb8 25. Nxa5 (25. Rxa5 $2 Rxb6 {
[%cal Gb6b3,Gd6d5,Gb6g6]}) (25. Bc1 Rxb6 26. Nd2 (26. Nxa5 $2 Rxb1 27. Rxb1
Nh4+ 28. Kf2 Nf5 29. Qg2 Qh4+ 30. Ke2 cxd4 31. cxd4 Qh5+ 32. Kf2 (32. Ke1 Nh4
$19) 32... Qd1 $19) 26... Nh4+ 27. Kh2 Rxb1 28. Rxb1 a4 $17) 25... Nxd2 26. Rb2
Nf3 27. Nc6 Nh4+ 28. Kh2 Rb7 29. Na5 Nf5 30. Qf2 Ne7 $1 (30... Re7 $143 31. b7
Bxb7 32. Rxb7 Re6 33. Nc6 Rh6 34. Qg2 Nxe3 35. Ne7+ Kh8 36. Qg3 Nf5 (36... Nxc4
$6 37. Rab1 {[%cal Gb7b8]}) 37. Nxf5 Qxf5 $13) 31. Nxb7 Qxh3+ 32. Kg1 Bxb7 $17)
18... a5 {In such situations is usually easier for Black to defend on b6 than
for White on a4.} 19. Rg1 Nh6 20. Bf1 Bd7 21. Bc1 Rac8 $5 {Before beginning
active operation on the kingside is preferable for Black to provoke d4-d5, and
although this move does not create any threats against c4-pawn White decided
to close the centre rather in result of psychological pressure.} 22. d5 $6 Kh8
$1 {Planning Rg8 followed by g7-g5.} 23. Nd2 ({Also hopeless for White was} 23.
Kg2 Rg8 24. Kf2 g5) 23... Rg8 24. Bg2 g5 25. Nf1 Rg7 {Black has a decisive
advantage due to the unsafe position of White`s king and weaknesses in his
pawn structure.} 26. Ra2 Nf5 27. Bh1 Rcg8 28. Qd1 ({In case of} 28. Rb2 Bxa4
29. Rxb6 Bc2 {[%cal Gc2d3] black bishop penetrated in White`s camp with
decisive effect.}) 28... gxf4 $1 29. exf4 Bc8 $1 30. Qb3 Ba6 {Nimzowitsch`s
play is very instructive. The idea of this manoeuvre is to deflect white queen
from the kingside.} 31. Re2 ({If White tries to defend g3-pawn by} 31. Bd2 Rg6
$1 32. Be1 {then wins} Bxc4 $1 33. Qxc4 Ng4+ $1 34. hxg4 hxg4+ 35. Kg2 e3 $19 {
[%cal Gh7h3]}) 31... Nh4 $1 {By opening the c8-h3 diagonal Black prepares to
attack on h3.} 32. Re3 ({To the nice mate led the continuation} 32. Nd2 Bc8 $1
33. Nxe4 (33. Qd1 Bxh3 $1 34. Nxe4 (34. Kxh3 Qf5+ $19) 34... Ng4+ $1 35. Kxh3
Qf5 {[%cal Gg4f2,Gf5h3]} 36. Kxh4 Ne3 37. Rxe3 Rg4+ 38. Kh3 Rxg3+ 39. Kh2 Qh3#)
33... Qf5 $1 34. Nf2 (34. g4 hxg4 $19) 34... Qxh3+ $1 35. Nxh3 Ng4#) 32... Bc8
$1 {[%cal Gc8h3,Gh7f5]} 33. Qc2 Bxh3 $1 34. Bxe4 (34. Kxh3 Qf5+ 35. g4 (35. Kh2
Ng4+ 36. Kh3 Nf2+ 37. Kh2 Qh3#) 35... Rxg4 36. Rxg4 Qxg4+ 37. Kh2 Qg1+ 38. Kh3
Qxf1+ $19) 34... Bf5 {The simplest.} 35. Bxf5 Nxf5 {[%cal Gh5h4]} 36. Re2 h4
37. Rgg2 hxg3+ 38. Kg1 Qh3 39. Ne3 Nh4 40. Kf1 Re8 $1 (40... Nf3 $1 $19) (40...
Re8 $1 {White resigned because after} 41. Nd1 (41. Qd1 Nxg2 42. Rxg2 Ng4 43.
Nxg4 Qh1+ 44. Rg1 g2+ 45. Kf2 Qh4+ $19) 41... Rgg8 $19 {he cannot parry
Black`s threats, e.g.} 42. Re3 (42. Qd3 Nxg2 43. Rxg2 Qh1+ 44. Rg1 g2+ 45. Kf2
Qh4+) 42... Nf3 $1 {[%cal Gh3h1]} 43. Rxf3 Qh1+ 44. Rg1 Qxf3+ 45. Nf2 g2+ 46.
