{[%evp 0,82,32,28,28,6,13,6,25,23,26,10,38,23,43,36,35,37,40,50,53,38,36,14,13,
3,32,11,6,6,5,-7,-7,-2,-4,3,4,7,19,15,18,30,28,11,4,4,50,-31,0,0,15,7,0,0,0,8,
37,0,25,26,37,14,15,0,28,13,0,24,12,-50,-46,-86,-57,-30,-73,-71,-76,-105,-112,
-113,-105,-113,-105,-127,-127] In the next few games, we shall take a look at
Black's light square strategy in positions with doubled pawns. This strategy
works in positions with closed centre. Let's take a look at a popular position
from the Huebner Variation arising after} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3
c5 5. Bd3 Nc6 6. Nf3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. O-O e5 9. Nd2 O-O 10. d5 $6 {Although
this is a very popular continuation, I consider it to be dubious. White's best
strategy is to keep the central tension as long as possible.} Ne7 11. e4 {
Let's try to figure out Black's best plan in this position. In the
introduction, we have pointed out that after giving his dark-squared bishop
for the c3-knight, Black should exchange the light-squared bishops as well as
a pair of knights. In this way, he is going to achieve a perfect attacking
tandem - queen + knight. Having only a dark-squared bishop, White will be
unable to neutralize Black's play on the light squares. In general, Black
should start his light-square strategy by preparing the advance ...f7-f5. For
that purpose, he plays} h6 $1 {[%cal Gf6h7,Gf7f5] preparing ...Nh7 followed by
... f7-f5. Later on, the knight can join the attack via the g5-square. The
next few moves are quite logical -} 12. Re1 Nh7 13. Nf1 f5 14. exf5 Bxf5 $1 {
Of course, we always take with the bishop. The idea is to exchange the
light-squared bishops.} 15. Ng3 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Qd7 {[%cal Gf8f7,Ga8f8,Ge7f5]
Black is preparing the double the rooks along the f-file. Additionally, at
some point, it's important to play ...Nf5 with the idea of exchanging the
remaining white knight.} 17. a4 Rf7 18. a5 Raf8 19. f3 Nf5 20. Nxf5 ({Black
usually answers} 20. Ne4 {with} Nf6 {insisting on the exchange of the knights.}
) 20... Rxf5 {This is a thematic position for such structures. In the long run,
Black will transfer all his pieces to the kingside. At some point, he can even
consider breaking White's defence by means of the advance ...g5-g4.} 21. Rb1
R8f7 22. Rb2 Qd8 {[%cal Gd8h4] The queen is heading to h4.} 23. Rxb7 {White is
trying to simplify in a slightly unpleasant endgame with good chances of a
draw,} Rxf3 24. gxf3 Rxb7 25. f4 Qh4 26. Qg3 Qxg3+ 27. hxg3 e4 $1 {Very nice
positional pawn sacrifice. Of course, Black should keep the c1-bishop closed
as long as possible.} 28. f5 Rb1 29. Kf1 Kf7 30. g4 Nf6 31. Bf4 Rxe1+ 32. Kxe1
Nxg4 33. Bxd6 a6 {Objectively speaking, this endgame should be a draw if White
plays precisely. His next move, however, is already a mistake.} 34. Bxc5 $2 (
34. Ke2 h5 35. Bxc5 h4 36. Bd6 h3 37. c5 h2 38. Bxh2 Nxh2 39. Ke3 Ke7 40. Kxe4
Kd7 $11) 34... Ne5 35. Bd4 Nxc4 $19 36. Kf2 g6 37. fxg6+ Kxg6 38. Bb6 Kf6 39.
Bc7 h5 40. Kg3 Kf5 41. Kf2 h4 0-1

