{[%evp 0,60,35,29,43,0,0,0,28,35,32,32,28,30,36,36,47,36,48,43,41,28,49,29,30,
15,24,15,20,-2,16,6,6,6,6,6,6,-11,-13,-21,0,-37,-34,-29,-6,-96,-96,-106,-106,
-106,-94,-93,-104,-157,-160,-179,-171,-205,-216,-412,-441,-29534,-29978] The
next example is even clearer illustration of Black's light-square strategy.
It's instructive to see how 2600-rated GM is outplayed without committing a
serious mistake.} 1. d4 e6 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. Bd3 Nc6 6. Nf3
Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. O-O e5 9. Nd2 O-O 10. Re1 {This time, White tries to keep
the central tension. Even though Black can win the d4-pawn, he shouldn't do
that because White's bishop pair might become very dangerous. A move that will
be useful in all cases is} h6 ({White's idea is well illustrated by the
following line -} 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 exd4 12. exd4 Nxd4 13. Bb2 $44 {with a
powerful compensation for the pawn.}) 11. d5 $2 {As we know, closing the
centre is a positional mistake.} ({White should keep the tension with} 11. Rb1)
11... Ne7 12. e4 Nh7 13. Rb1 b6 {[%cal Gf7f5] Black is now ready to follow
with ...f7-f5.} 14. Rb2 f5 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. Bxf5 Nxf5 17. Ne4 {Do you
remember how we should deal with the e4-knight?} Nf6 {Of course! After
exchanging White's remaining knight, Black can follow with his light square
strategy.} 18. Qd3 Nxe4 19. Rxe4 Qf6 {[%cal Gf6g6,Ga8e8,Ge8e7,Ge7f7] Just like
in the previous example, Black is planning to double the rooks along the
f-file. Of course, the queen is heading for the kingside. The g6-square would
be a good square for the queen.} 20. g3 {Trying to restrict the knight but
weakening the light squares.} Rae8 21. Rbe2 Re7 22. h4 $2 {After this move,
Black manages to develop a dangerous attack.} ({Better would have been} 22. f4
Ref7 23. fxe5 dxe5 24. Rf2 Re7 $132 {with a complicated fight to follow.})
22... Qg6 23. Kh2 Ref7 24. Qc2 Rf6 {[%cal Gg6f7] preparing ...Qf7.} 25. Kh3 Qf7
26. Qd3 Ne7 {White's position is already very difficult. He lost in a few
moves.} 27. Be3 Rf3 28. Kg2 Nf5 29. Qc2 Qg6 30. h5 Rxg3+ 0-1

