-84,-113,-113,-201,-130,-214,-185,-228,-177,-290,-315,-459,-185,-354,-354] In
the next example, we shall take a look at another typical strategy that Black
can utilize - closing the kingside and start playing on the other wing.} 1. d4
Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 d6
9. e4 e5 10. d5 Ne7 11. h3 {With this move, and the next one, White tries to
restrict Black's minor pieces. This strategy, however, is dubious since it
leads to kingside weaknesses.} Ng6 12. g3 Bd7 13. Kf1 h6 {[%cal Gf6h7,Gf7f5]
Black opts for his usual strategy - ...Nh7 followed by ...f7-f5.} 14. Ra2 Nh7
15. g4 {Stopping ...f7-f5 but weakening the dark squares on the kingside.} Qf6
16. Ng1 {[%cal Gf2f3,Ga2f2] White is planning to proceed with f2-f3 followed
by Rf2. Later on, he can even think of advancing his kingside pawns.} Nh4 17.
f3 Rfb8 {[%cal Gb7b5] After blocking the kingside, Black starts playing on the
queenside. With his last move, Khismatullin prepares the advance ...b7-b5.} 18.
Rf2 g5 $1 {Stopping f3-f4. Now, Black has a free hand on the queenside.} 19.
Ne2 a6 20. Ng3 b5 21. Nf5 Bxf5 22. exf5 bxc4 23. Be4 Rb3 $19 {[%cal Gf6d8,
Gd8a5] The battle on the queenside is already won for Black. Now, he is
