{[%evp 0,88,20,20,27,-10,-10,12,25,23,28,-9,-10,-10,-3,-3,14,14,28,24,24,17,36,
34,69,-53,-16,-74,-6,-44,-34,-34,-31,-44,-38,-44,-35,-127,-141,-139,-138,-138,
-79,-79,-82,-153,-153,-171,-189,-197,-172,-238,-197,-213,-206,-231,-228,-279,
-272,-296,-286,-313,-293,-345,-311,-395,-550,-595,-509,-535,-278,-467,-476,
-482,-514,-485,-508,-555,-604,-618,-613,-640,-617,-638,-678,-691,-702,-656,
-656,-656,-541] After studying how to fight against doubled pawns in positions
with classical closed centre, we shall take a look at some lines in which
White gets full control over the centre. In the current game, GM Pavel Eljanov
demonstrated a wonderful strategy aiming to restrict the minor pieces of his
opponent.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 {
[%cal Gf1d3,Ge3e4,Gg1e2,Gf2f4] Since White didn't play Nf3, he wants to build
a strong centre by means of Bd3 and Ne2 followed by e3-e4 and f2-f4.} b6 ({
More traditional move order is} 6... c5 7. Bd3 Nc6 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gb7b6,
Gc8a6] Putting pressure on d4. Afterwards, Black follows with ...b7-b6 and ...
Ba6.}) 7. Bd3 Bb7 {The idea of this move order is to provoke the advance f2-f3.
In this way, White cannot put the pawn on f4 in one go. Additionally, in some
lines, especially after e4-e5, due to the pawn on f3, the white queen cannot
go to the kingside.} 8. f3 c5 9. Ne2 Nc6 10. e4 {[%cal Gc1g5,Gh4d8] We have
arrived at the first critical position for this setup. With his last move,
White prepares the annoying Bg5. The pin would be very dangerous for Black.
That's why, whenever White is ready to play Bg5, you should go for the thematic
} Ne8 $1 11. O-O Na5 {Now, Black starts his thematic play against the c4-pawn.
The pressure can be increased with different moves such as ...Rc8, ...Ba6, or
even ...Nd6.} 12. f4 {[%cal Gf4f5,Gf5f6] This is the second critical position.
Pushing the f-pawn all the way to f6 is one of the most thematic attacking
ideas. That's why, in response to ...f3-f4, Black should immediately play} f5
$1 {[%csl Rc1,Rd3,Gf5] Remember this move. Black fixes the f4-pawn and
restricts all the white minor pieces. The f5-pawn restricts the d3-bishop and
the knight while the f4-pawn restricts the dark-squared bishop and the knight.}
13. Ng3 Nd6 {[%csl Rc4] Protecting f5 and attacking the c4-pawn. White is now
forced to release the central tension. A very instructive position arises after
} 14. exf5 exf5 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Rb1 Qc7 17. Re1 g6 $19 {[%csl Rc1,Rc4,Rd3,
Gf5,Rg3,Gg6,Gh7] The point of Black's previous play. Black has no way to
activate his minor pieces. Additionally, the c4-pawn is doomed. Black has a
winning advantage that Eljanov managed to convert.} 18. Bf1 Rae8 19. Be3 Ndxc4
20. Bf2 Rxe1 21. Qxe1 d6 22. Qd1 Qf7 23. a4 Bc6 24. Ne2 Qd7 25. h4 Bxa4 26. Qd3
Bc6 27. Ra1 Be4 28. Qg3 Nb3 29. Rd1 Nbd2 30. Qg5 Qg7 31. Ra1 Nxf1 32. Kxf1 Bd3
33. Rd1 Qxc3 34. Qe7 Qf6 35. Qxa7 Qb2 36. Rxd3 Qb1+ 37. Be1 Qxd3 38. Bc3 Ne3+
39. Kg1 Qd1+ 40. Kh2 Ng4+ 41. Kh3 Nf2+ 42. Kg3 Ne4+ 43. Kh2 Nxc3 44. Nxc3 Qd4
0-1

