{So far, we have been dealing with cases where White immediately clarifies the
situation in the centre. In this game, Karpov demonstrates an interesting
strategy that can be applied when White keeps the tension. I call his approach
"blockade on the light squares". At this point, Karpov goes for the following
sequence -} 13... cxd4 $1 14. cxd4 d5 15. cxd5 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 fxe4 17. Qxe4 Qxd5
18. Qxd5 exd5 {[%csl Rd4,Rf4][%cal Ge8d6] A beautiful illustration of Black's
light square strategy. White's minor pieces are completely restricted.
Additionally, e4 and c4-squares are perfect spots for black knights. The
queenside pawn majority is a very important advantage as well.} 19. Rac1 Rc8
20. f5 {White should play this move before Black's ...Nd6.} Nd6 21. fxg6 hxg6
22. Rxf8+ Kxf8 {Finally, the position has been clarified. Black is better due
to his good central control and queenside pawn majority. Even though White has
some chances for a draw, Karpov managed to score a nice win.} 23. h4 Nc4 24.
Bg5 Nxd4 25. h5 gxh5 26. Rf1+ Ke8 27. Nxh5 Nxa3 28. Ng7+ Kd7 29. Rf7+ Kc6 30.
Rxa7 Nac2 31. Bf6 b5 32. g4 b4 33. Ra2 b3 34. Rb2 Kc5 35. Nf5 Rg8 36. Nxd4
Rxg4+ 37. Kf2 Nxd4 38. Bxd4+ Kxd4 39. Rxb3 Re4 40. Ra3 Re8 0-1

