{[%evp 0,78,27,27,28,5,-10,-11,25,22,28,-3,-3,-3,16,10,12,9,9,14,13,-12,62,-3,
33,-31,51,18,21,-10,-49,-71,-76,-153,-171,-200,-192,-193,-204,-294,-285,-292,
-268,-305,-262,-250,-290,-327,-327,-295,-304,-331,-379,-338,-338,-360,-413,
-399,-399,-564,-574,-565,-563,-588,-639,-625,-539,-623,-631,-619,-619,-667,
-546,-663,-559,-687,-687,-29993,-29994,-29995,-29996] In this example, we will
see how to parry White's attack when it's impossible to answer f4 with ...
f7-f5. We are already familiar with the first 10 moves.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 7. Bd3 Nc6 8. Ne2 b6 9. O-O Ba6 10. e4
{[%cal Gc1g5]} Ne8 {Now, instead of the usual f2-f4, White decided to start
with} 11. Ng3 {Anticipating Black's ...f7-f5. On the other hand, in many cases,
the g3-knight is going to be misplaced.} Na5 ({As usual, we refrain from
taking the d4-pawn. For example, after} 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 Nxd4 13. Bb2 $44 {
White gets more than enough compensation for the pawn.}) 12. f4 f6 $1 {A very
important move. Remember that when ...f7-f5 is not possible, you should play ..
.f7-f6.} 13. f5 {With a knight on g3, this idea is not dangerous. It would
have been a different story if White had the opportunity to follow with Nf4.
Now, Black can take the c4-pawn without any fears -} Bxc4 14. Bxc4 Nxc4 {
[%csl Ge8,Gf6] Pay attention to the powerful defensive construction Ne8&f6.
When you manage to achieve it, you will never get checkmated, even if White
finally takes on h7 with the queen.} 15. Rf4 {[%cal Gf4h4,Gd1h5] White is
planning to proceed with Rh4 followed by Qh5.} ({Another game saw} 15. Qe2 b5
16. a4 {Now, Black should have played} cxd4 17. cxd4 a6 $17 {with a healthy
extra pawn.}) 15... cxd4 16. Rh4 $2 {As you already know, in this position,
White's attack is an illusion.} ({Nevertheless, even after} 16. cxd4 b5 {
[%cal Ge8d6] White does not have compensation for the pawn.}) 16... dxc3 17.
Qh5 Qc7 {We are not afraid of Qxh7.} 18. Qxh7+ Kf7 19. Qh5+ Ke7 $19 {The king
is safe and Black is winning.} 20. Qe2 Rc8 21. a4 Qe5 22. fxe6 dxe6 23. Bf4
Qd4+ 24. Kh1 c2 25. Rc1 Ne5 26. h3 Qd3 27. Qe1 g5 28. Rh7+ Rf7 29. Bxe5 Rxh7
30. Bb2 g4 31. h4 Rxh4+ 32. Kg1 Rh6 33. Qf2 Qd1+ 34. Nf1 Nd6 35. e5 Nf5 36. Qf4
g3 37. exf6+ Kf7 38. Qe4 Rch8 39. Qb7+ Kg6 0-1

