{In the next few examples, we will examine how Black should deal with the
advance f2-f4 in positions with a closed centre. It's a very important topic
since one needs to know whether to go for ...exf4 or keep the central tension.
The first game features one of the most important positions in the Huebner
Variation -} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. Bd3 Nc6 6. Nf3 Bxc3+ 7.
bxc3 d6 8. e4 e5 9. d5 Ne7 10. Nh4 {This is the only reasonable way to justify
the advance d4-d5. Now, White prepares both Bg5 and f2-f4. Black, however, has
a thematic response at his disposal -} h6 11. O-O O-O 12. f4 Ng6 $1 {This is
the point. As we will see, by allowing the exchange on g6, Black actually
improves his pawn structure.} ({When White's dark-squared bishop is on the
board, taking on f4 is not a good option. For example, after} 12... exf4 13.
Bxf4 {White is clearly better due to his central control and attacking
prospects on the kingside.}) 13. Nxg6 fxg6 14. fxe5 dxe5 {Remember this
typical pawn structure. Despite White's protected passer and Black's doubled
pawns, Black's chances are already preferable. A closer look at the position
shows that White has no way to activate his bishops. On, the other hand, Black
has a good play on the kingside. Later on, he will expand with ...g6-g5
followed by doubling the rooks on the f-file and transferring the knight to f4.
Additionally, the c8-bishop is controlling the entire board.} 15. Rb1 b6 16. h3
Bd7 17. Be3 Qe8 $1 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Gg6g5,Gf6h5,Gh5f4] A multi-purpose move.
From e8, the queen controls the important a4-square, thus making the advance
a2-a4-a5 impossible. At the same time, after ...g6-g5, Black can consider
playing ...Nh5.} 18. Bc2 Rb8 19. Rb2 g5 20. g4 $2 {This move is already a
mistake. White tries to prevent ...Nh5, but the black knight has an
alternative route to f4.} Nh7 21. a4 Rxf1+ 22. Kxf1 a5 $1 {Before proceeding
with his own play, Spiridonov neutralizes the active possibilities of his
opponent.} 23. Kg2 Qf8 24. Qg1 Qd6 25. Bf2 Nf8 26. Bg3 Ng6 27. Qe1 Rf8 {
Black has accomplished all the desired manoeuvres. Now, his position is
strategically winning.} 28. Qb1 Rf6 29. Bd1 Nf4+ 30. Kh2 g6 31. Rf2 Be8 32. Bc2
h5 33. gxh5 gxh5 34. h4 g4 35. Qe1 Qf8 36. Qe3 Kg7 37. Qd2 Ng6 38. Rf5 Rxf5 39.
exf5 Nf4 40. Bxf4 exf4 41. Qxf4 Qe7 42. Qg5+ Qxg5 43. hxg5 h4 44. f6+ Kf7 45.
Bf5 g3+ 46. Kh3 Bxa4 47. d6 g2 48. Kh2 h3 49. Bxh3 Be8 50. d7 1-0

