{[%evp 0,76,28,18,30,19,-10,16,25,-26,-13,-13,-4,12,25,24,34,-1,-15,2,18,25,23,
23,39,32,44,44,45,29,39,21,15,15,21,-80,-41,-116,-110,-127,-126,-114,-125,-146,
-111,-115,-92,-123,-119,-140,-139,-145,-135,-145,-135,-145,-90,-164,-149,-185,
-153,-148,-163,-148,-168,-152,-145,-194,-196,-196,-191,-278,-267,-345,-334,
-349,-351,-386,-361] The next game features an interesting line which Black
can use against the system with 4.g3. The critical position arises after} 1. d4
Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. Nf3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. Qd3 e5
9. Nd2 Qe7 10. O-O Re8 11. e4 b6 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6] In such positions, Black's
strategy is rather simple. He needs to keep the centre stable and develop his
queenside play. The last move is designed to prepare ...Ba6 followed by ...Na5.
} 12. Ba3 Ba6 13. f4 {Now, White is threatening to take on e5. Therefore,
Black should decide how to handle the central tension. As a rule, when White
has a bishop pair, you should let him clarify the central situation. 
Chuchelov played} Qd7 {A right idea that was not executed in the best
redaction.} ({More to the point would have been} 13... Qd8 $1 {It's important
to keep the f6-knight overprotected. The game might continue -} 14. Rf2 {
[%cal Ga1f1]} ({After} 14. Rf3 {Black has the following tactical motif at his
disposal:} Na5 15. Raf1 $2 Nxc4 16. Nxc4 d5 17. exd5 e4 $19) 14... Na5 15. Bb4
Nb7 16. Raf1 c5 {A thematic move in this pawn structure. Black fixes the
c4-pawn and further restricts White's dark-squared bishop. Additionally, After
...Rc8 and ...Na5, he can initiate play along the c-file. After} 17. Ba3 Ng4
18. Rf3 Na5 19. fxe5 dxe5 20. d5 {Black has the following thematic idea -} (20.
Rxf7 exd4 {[%cal Gg4e5]}) 20... f6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gg4h6,Gh6f7,Gf7d6]
Whenever the d6-square is available, you should try to bring your knight there.
With his last move, Black prepares the manoeuvre...Nh6-f7-d6.} 21. Bh3 Nh6 $15
{[%cal Gh6f7,Gf7d6]}) 14. fxe5 dxe5 15. d5 Na5 16. Bb4 Nb7 17. Rxf6 {This move
is the reason why I prefer ...Qd8. Even though Black managed to win the game,
White retains some compensation.} gxf6 18. Qf1 c5 19. Bh3 Qe7 20. Ba3 Nd6 21.
Qf3 Kh8 22. Rf1 Rg8 23. Bf5 Rg5 24. Bc1 Rag8 25. Bh3 R5g6 26. Bf5 R6g7 27. Bh3
Rg5 28. Re1 R5g6 29. Nf1 Bxc4 30. Ne3 Bxa2 31. Nf5 Qd8 32. Nxd6 Qxd6 33. Bf5
