{[#] This position was reached in my game against the Romanian IM Vladimir
Danilov. Once again, White is planning to initiate a kingside attack by means
of f2-f4. Probably, his next move will be f4-f5. Since White does not have a
dark-squared bishop, I played} 15. f4 exf4 16. Rxf4 Qe5 {Now, the queen is
pretty safe on e5. White's play on the f-file is not enough to compensate him
for his multiple structural weaknesses. In the future, after stabilizing the
position, Black is going to initiate a queenside play by means of ...b7-b5.}
17. Raf1 Bd7 18. Qf3 f6 {[%cal Gb7b5] All pawns on dark squares! White does
not have any active play on the kingside. The advance ...b7-b5 is coming.} 19.
g4 b5 20. h4 bxc4 $19 {Black's position is already strategically winning.
Unfortunately, due to my imprecise play in the endgame, I missed the advantage.
} 21. g5 hxg5 22. hxg5 Qxg5+ 23. Kf2 f5 24. Rg1 Qh6 25. e5 dxe5 26. Rh1 Qg6 27.
Rfh4 f4 28. Rg1 Qf5 29. Rh5 Qd3 30. Qh1 Bf5 31. Rh8+ Kf7 32. Qh5+ Bg6 33. Rxf8+
Rxf8 34. Qxe5 Re8 35. Qxf4+ Kg8 36. Qg4 Qe3+ 37. Kf1 Re4 38. Rg3 Qd2 39. Qf3
Bf5 40. Kf2 Qxd5 41. Rg5 g6 42. Rg1 Qd2 43. Re1 Qd3 44. Qg3 Qxg3+ 45. Nxg3 Rxe1
46. Kxe1 Kf7 47. Kf2 Kf6 48. Ke3 Ke5 49. Nf1 Bb1 50. a3 Bd3 51. Nh2 Kd5 52. Ng4
Bf5 53. Nh2 Kc6 54. Kd2 g5 55. Nf1 Bd3 56. Ng3 Kd5 57. Ke3 Ke5 58. Kf3 Bf5 59.
Ke3 g4 60. Ne2 Be4 61. Ng3 Bd3 62. Nh5 1/2-1/2

