case? (See the solution in the comments to the game Flores, D - Bu, X)}  *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Nimzo Indian"]
[Black "Light Squares"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E43"]
[Annotator "GM Mihail Marin"]
[PlyCount "18"]
[EventDate "2021.09.04"]
[Source "ChessPublishing"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {[%csl Rd5,Re4] With this move, Black weakens
White's control over the important light squares on d5 and e4. His main
intention might seem to be precisely to play on light squares, but as you can
find out in the webinars held by other grandmasters, several other global
plans could derivate from here. I will illustrate now some of the main
patterns.} 4. e3 (4. Qc2 {prepares to get the bishop's pair without spoiling
the structure with bxc3. However, this implies spending two more tempi on
a2-a3 and Qxc3, while also weakening two more light squares, those on b3 and,
indirectly, on c4.} O-O (4... c5 {may lead to a different situation, where
White will get the aforementioned weaknesses without forcing Black to give up
the bishops' pair.} 5. dxc5 O-O 6. a3 Bxc5 7. Nf3 b6 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 Bb7 10.
Rd1 Be7 11. e4 Nc6 {[%csl Rb3,Rc4][%cal Ga8c8,Gc6a5]}) 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 {
[%csl Gb3,Gc4] White has achieved his aim, but is slightly behind in
development and the queenside structure requires certain attention. Moreover,
the queen is likely to cause more waste of time soon, as she is exposed on c3.
However in the following line (an important one, but not the only one
available to White), Black would mainly play for the light squares along the
light diagonal.} b6 7. Nf3 Bb7 8. e3 Ne4 9. Qc2 f5) 4... b6 {Openly playing
for the light squares along the long diagonal.} ({The central plan} 4... O-O 5.
Bd3 d5 6. Nf3 c5 7. O-O Nc6 {puts the focus on different light squares.} 8. a3
Bxc3 9. bxc3 Qc7 10. cxd5 exd5 {[%cal Gc5c4,Ge3e4] White will try to advance
his centre with e3-e4 (usually prepared bu f2-f3), while Black would be glad
to exchange the light-squared bishops. Black could choose between blocking
with ...c5-c4 and opening the c-file in order to get an outpost on c4.}) 5. Bd3
Bb7 6. Nf3 Ne4 7. Qc2 f5 8. O-O Bxc3 9. bxc3 O-O {Black is slightly behind in
development, but his control along the long diagonal offers him some attacking
chances.} *

