{We will start by examining a few aspects connected with the fight for the
light squares along the long diagonal.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 b6
5. Bd3 Bb7 6. Nf3 Ne4 7. O-O $5 {Practice has shown that this is more
promising than defending the pawn.} (7. Qc2 {offers Black an important tempo.}
f5 8. O-O Bxc3 9. bxc3 O-O 10. Ne1 c5 11. f3 Nd6) 7... Bxc3 (7... Nxc3 8. bxc3
Bxc3 9. Rb1 {leaves the dark-squared bishop exposed and passive.}) 8. bxc3 f5 (
8... Nxc3 {fails to force a perpetual check.} 9. Qc2 Bxf3 10. gxf3 Qg5+ 11. Kh1
Qh5 12. Rg1 $1 Qxf3+ 13. Rg2 f5 14. Ba3 $1 {with overwhelming compensation for
the pawns.}) 9. Ne1 $1 O-O (9... Nxc3 {wastes too much developing time,
yielding White strong initiative.} 10. Qc2 Ne4 11. f3 Nd6 12. c5 Nf7 13. e4)
10. f3 Ng5 {White has managed to reduce Black's influence over the light
squares, but the tension along the long diagonal remains alive. I remembered
that White's plan should include e3-e4 and Nc2-e3, but was not sure about the
move order. It is funny that while making my plans, I was constantly concerned
about keeping f3 defended... This did not prevent me from going wrong, though.}
11. Nc2 $6 (11. c5 $5 bxc5 $6 12. Ba3) (11. Qe2 d6 (11... Nc6 12. e4 fxe4 13.
fxe4 Rxf1+ 14. Qxf1 e5 15. Nc2) 12. e4 fxe4 13. Bxg5 $1 (13. fxe4 Rxf1+ 14.
Kxf1 Nd7 15. Kg1 Qe7 16. Nc2 Rf8 {with at least equal chances for Black, who
maintains the pressure along the long diagonal.}) 13... Qxg5 (13... exd3 14.
Qxe6+) 14. Bxe4 {In this line, the natural move ...d7-d6 does a bad service to
Black in two moments. In the sub-line above, it allows a decisive intermediate
check and in the final position it leaves the pawn on e6 weak.}) 11... d6 12.
Re1 $2 {After playing this move, I immediately noticed Black's combination.} (
12. d5 {is a typical way of fighting for the light squares, but here it is not
promising.} Na6 $1 {Development above all! Black has some stability on dark
squares now.} (12... exd5 $2 13. cxd5 Bxd5 14. Nd4 g6 15. h4 Nf7 16. e4 $16)
13. Nd4 Nc5 $11) 12... Nd7 $6 {My opponent played this after a long thought.} (
{I was relieved that he did not notice} 12... Bxf3 $1 {With incomplete
development, this looks unnatural, of course, but it is an excellent
illustration of the strength of Black's pressure along the long diagonal.} 13.
gxf3 Nh3+ 14. Kf1 (14. Kh1 Nf2+) (14. Kg2 Qg5+ 15. Kxh3 Rf6) 14... Qg5 {
It appears that all the white pieces situated in the immediate neighbourhood
of the king only prevent him from escaping, without providing him with any
help.} 15. Qd2 Qg1+ 16. Ke2 Qg2+ 17. Kd1 Nf2+ 18. Ke2 Ne4+) 13. e4 f4 14. h4
Nf7 15. Bxf4 Qxh4 16. Qd2 1/2-1/2

