{[%evp 0,66,25,0,0,0,0,14,28,28,28,-14,3,-15,-7,-16,-21,-18,-17,-6,-15,-13,-19,
-19,-17,-4,-12,0,-3,-24,-43,-37,5,1,0,-3,-3,-7,-7,0,-7,0,20,25,27,-71,-150,
-478,-488,-467,-494,-485,-490,-498,-498,-499,-497,-794,-879,-1351,-29988,
-29991,-29992,-29993,-29994,-29995,-29994,-29995,-29996] Simagin's comments to
this fine game are marked with V.S., while mine with M.M.} 1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 Nf6
3. d4 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6 5. Qc2 Bb7 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 O-O 8. e3 {Play transposed
to a positional variation of the 4.Qc2 system. Black's knight belongs to e4,
but SImagin chooses a move order considered as best up to today.} d6 9. b4 ({
The modern main continuation is} 9. Be2 Nbd7 10. O-O Ne4 11. Qc2 f5 12. b4 Rf6
13. Bb2 Rg6 14. d5 $1 {White has to obstruct the enemy bishop before the
attack becomes too strong. If Black accepts the sacrifice, White will obtain
strong initiative, but} c5 $1 {, preventing the invasion on e6 with Nd4 keeps
things under control.}) ({The seemingly active} 9. Bd3 Nbd7 10. O-O {allows}
Bxf3 11. gxf3 Nh5 {with excellent kingside play. More about all these in my
Nimzo-Indian repertoire, published by Modern Chess.}) 9... Nbd7 10. Bb2 Ne4 11.
Qc2 f5 {The game develops along a well known strategic scheme. Black's setup
reminds us of some Dutch Defence lines. (V.S.)} 12. Be2 Ng5 $1 {A tactical
operation with the purpose of preventing White from castling short. After the
correct continuation, this would not have yielded Black an advantage. (V.S.)}
13. c5 {Most commentators criticized this move, but, apparently, in vain.} ({
Of course, there were other possibilities, for instance} 13. Qd1 {with
satisfactory play. (A much later game abruptly ended in a draw after} f4 {
Akobian-Venkatesh, Phpadelphia 2005. Black has promising initiative. M.M.)}) ({
Romanovsky's recommendation} 13. O-O-O {is highly questionable. AFter} Ne4 $1
14. Bd3 Qe7 {followed by 15...c5 Black easily generates a winning attack
against the white king (V.S.) Simagin's evaluation may be a bit exaggerated,
but Black surely has an advantage. Other promising continuations are} ({
the immediate} 14... c5 {and}) (14... b5 $5 15. cxb5 c6 16. bxc6 Bxc6 17. Kb1
Bd5 $15 {with dangerous initiative. Kortschnoj's decision to react to the
kingside attack with a counterblow on the opposite wing is principled, but in
this concrete case not very effective. (M.M.)})) 13... Be4 14. Qc3 {This is
the first serious mistake. The queen steps away onto an unfavourable position
and this will be the cause of White's later difficulties.} ({White should have
played} 14. Qd1 {. Here is an illustrative variation:} Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Nxf3+ 16.
Qxf3 dxc5 17. dxc5 bxc5 18. O-O {and White could reach a draw without special
difficulties. (V.S.)}) ({After} 14. Qd1 {Black can do better than giving away
his bishop with} Nxf3+ $1 15. Bxf3 ({Against Simagin's 14...Bxf3, White could
consider} 15. gxf3 {, but here this is simply bad due to the calm} Bd5 $17 {
with perfect control on light squares.}) 15... Qh4) 14... Bd5 15. c6 $2 {
This move is not very appealing, of course, but opening the c-file would
favour Black now. Even now, White's position remains defensible. The decisive
mistake is still ahead. Owing to its spectacular end, this game was published
in many chess magazines, but its course did not receive proper coverage.} ({
For instance, in the article dedicated to the 27th USSR championship,
Romanovsky recommends the pawn sacrifice} 15. Nd2 {as White's last chance.
However, after} Bxg2 16. Rg1 Bd5 $1 {White's position is completely hopeless.
Kortschnoj totally correctly decided that there were no reasons for concern
yet. (V.S.) Actually, Romanovsky was right. After} 17. c6 Nb8 18. b5 {the
knight is caged and White has enough compensation for the pawn. For instance}
a6 19. a4 Ne4 20. Nxe4 fxe4 21. Kf1 Rf5 22. Rg3 Qf6 23. Qe1 {and Black can do
little more than hold his position. At a later moment he may consider ...Nxc6,
getting three pawns for the knight, but this would hardly yield him an
advantage.}) ({Moreover, after} 15. Nd2 Bxg2 {White can deviate from Simagin's
line with the intermediate move} 16. d5 $5 e5 17. Rg1 Bxd5 ({Alternatively,} 
17... Ne4 18. Nxe4 Bxe4 19. O-O-O {with double-edged play, due to the central
tension.}) 18. c6 Nb8 19. f4 Ne6 20. b5 Qh4+ 21. Rg3 {Black has to find a way
of dealing with White's pressure on e5 and g7.}) (15. Nd2 {In all these lines,
there is a certain danger for Black. Therefore, he could reject the pawn
sacrifice with} Ne4 16. Nxe4 fxe4 {maintaining his stability on light squares
and certain attacking chances. (M.M.)}) 15... Ne4 {Black has to release the
tension in order to play ...Nf6.} ({The other way of doing it was} 15... Nxf3+
16. gxf3 Nf6 $15 {(M.M.)}) 16. Qc1 Ndf6 17. O-O Qe8 18. b5 Qh5 19. Qd1 Qh6 (
19... Ng5 $5) 20. a4 ({After} 20. Nd2 {the outcome of the game would be quite
unclear, as Black does not have irresistible threats at his disposal. (V.S.)
Simagin greatly underestimates the strength of his attack. Black does have
very strong threats after} Ng4 $1 21. Bxg4 (21. h3 {allows} Nxe3 22. fxe3 Qxe3+
23. Kh2 {Taking the knight would be good enough, but Black can do even better.}
Qg3+ 24. Kg1 Nc3 {winning the queen.}) 21... Nxd2 22. Qxd2 fxg4 {Black
threatens to set up a simple, but decisive, attack along the h-file with ...
Rf6, ...Qh4 and ...Rh6, with ...Bf3 a permanent resource, of course.} 23. Qd3 {
is the only way to cross this plan, but it does not save the game:} Rf6 24. e4
Qg6 25. Rae1 Rf4 $19 {Black wins the e4-pawn and retains dangerous kingside
threats. Despite Simagin's evaluation, the only real mistake is 15.c6. (M.M.)})
20... Ng4 $1 21. h3 Rf6 $1 {A decisive sacrifice. (V.S.)} 22. hxg4 {White is
forced to accept the sacrifice, as Black threatened 22...Rg6. (V.S.)} ({
Here is an illustrative line:} 22. a5 Raf8 ({Better than the immediate} 22...
Rg6 23. axb6 {with certain counter chances.}) 23. axb6 axb6 24. Ra3 {This and
the next move aim at consolidating e3.} Rg6 25. Bc1 Nxe3 $1 $19 {Anyway! Black
will play ...Qxh3 next. (M.M.)}) 22... fxg4 23. Nh2 {Black threatened 24...Qh5
and 26...Rh6. (V.S.)} Nxf2 $1 {The point of Black's combination consists of
this uncomplicated blow. The events develop by force. (V.S.) This is the first
moment when we see the principle enounced by Bronstein in practice: the
general weakness of the light squares results in the weakness of the dark
squares. (M.M)} (23... g3 {, suggested during the webinar, is insufficient due
to} 24. Ng4 gxf2+ 25. Rxf2 $18) 24. Rxf2 g3 25. Ng4 ({If} 25. Nf3 {the
decisive line goes:} Qxe3 26. Qe1 Rh6 27. Kf1 Rh1+ 28. Ng1 Bxg2+ 29. Rxg2 Rf8+
30. Bf3 Qxf3+ 31. Rf2 g2# {(V.S.)}) 25... gxf2+ 26. Nxf2 Qxe3 27. Qe1 Raf8 28.
Bf3 Rxf3 $1 29. gxf3 Qxf3 30. Kf1 Bc4+ 31. Kg1 Qg3+ 32. Kh1 Bd5+ 33. Ne4 Rf1+
$1 0-1

