{[%evp 0,65,19,31,14,-14,-11,-9,-3,28,34,14,45,44,44,44,37,32,33,34,43,17,19,
13,60,41,120,16,-3,-18,-13,-20,-102,-127,-133,-136,-48,-62,-55,-41,-3,8,22,23,
23,23,36,49,40,19,47,107,131,93,248,55,64,91,115,93,93,93,309,355,452,508,703,
681]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6 5. e3 Ne4 6. Qc2 Bb7 7. Bd3 Bxc3+
8. bxc3 f5 9. O-O O-O 10. a4 Nc6 11. Ba3 {Both sides' intentions are clear.
Black has built up some kingside space advantage and can think of taking
advantage of the weakness on c4 if White prematurely wins a pawn on e4. White
should aim at opening files on the queenside or else restrict the bishop on b7
with d4-d5. Additionally, he can consider driving the e4-knight away with Ne1
and f2-f3.} Rf6 $1 {The first committal move, speaking about Black's
aggressive intentions. If Black's attack will not prove consistent enough, the
rook will remain out of play for a long while.} 12. Rfb1 {White mechanically
concentrates his forces on the queenside, without any clear perspective of
making progress.} ({If} 12. Bxe4 fxe4 13. Qxe4 Na5 14. d5 (14. Qd3 $2 Rxf3 $1 {
wins at once}) 14... Qe8 $5 $15 {Black can combine kingside threats with the
pressure on the chronically weak pawn on c4.}) 12... Rb8 $5 13. Bb4 Rg6 14. Bf1
Rh6 {After inducing White to release the pressure on e4, Black switches to the
most aggressive plan.} 15. Rd1 {Trying to switch to a more concrete plan:
d4-d5.} g5 $1 {The logical sequel of the previous rook manoeuvre. Black needs
to drive the f3-knight away in order to create threats along the h-file.} 16.
Nd2 ({Sadly, White does not have the time for} 16. d5 $2 {due to} Nxb4 17. cxb4
g4 18. Ne5 Qh4 $19) 16... g4 17. g3 {Black has achieved a dream position.
White has now weaknesses on light squares all over the board and his king is
very poorly defended. But at this height, Vallejo seems to have completely
lost the sense of danger. His position is obviously close to winning, but also
requires concrete action to get the full point.} Nxb4 $4 {This is a good
candidate for the worst move ever in a won position. I do not refer only to
the fact that it helps White improving his queenside structure, as this is of
secondary importance from the perspective of the kingside play. Black
obviously wanted to clear the long diagonal for his bishop, but he could have
done this at a later stage of the attack, either with ...Nxb4 or ...Nxd4.
Exchanging the knight is too high a commitment, as White can now count on
reducing the intensity of the attack with d4-d5, without fearing that Black
would bring in new resources with ...Ne5. But this exchange is only the first
in a series of uninspired moves, turning a promising position into a
strategically doomed one.} ({AN experienced player should consider one
candidate only:} 17... Nxf2 $1 18. Kxf2 Rxh2+ {starting a virtually winning
attack against the poorly defended white king. This is the kind of attack one
should not try to calculate until the end (maybe this is what Vallejo did,
leading him to the conclusion that things are not clear), especially that
Black has a draw by perpetual in his pocket as seen below.} 19. Kg1 (19. Ke1 {
is even worse, if there really is a place for that:} Qg5 20. Qd3 e5 {and due
to the threat ...e5-e4 White cannot defend e3 for long. After the king retreat
to g1, Black even has a choice about how to continue his attack.}) {In order
to avoid the simplifying manoeuvre and decide the game by a direct attack, the
queen should choose a different route:} 19... Rh1+ $1 {But first Black has to
remove the rook from the attacked square.} ({For practical reasons, the
simplest is} 19... Qg5 $5 {threatening both ...Qh6 and 20...Qxe3+ 21.Kxh2 Nxb4
followed by ...Qf2+. Objectively, it is not the absolutely strongest as White
can try to survive in a clearly inferior position with} 20. Nf3 (20. Kxh2 $2
Qh6+ 21. Kg1 Qxe3+ 22. Kh2 Nxb4 23. cxb4 Qf2+) 20... Rxc2 21. Nxg5 h6 22. Nxe6
dxe6 $17 {and Black has "only" a material and positional advantage.}) 20. Kf2 {
As we can see, Black had the perpetual check safety net.} Qf6 $1 {[%cal Gh1h2,
Gf6h6] Threatening with the familiar ...Qh6.} 21. Bg2 Rh2 22. Rg1 ({In a
similar line that could have arisen after the premature exchange on b4, White
would repel the attack and win with d4-d5. But here this does not save:} 22. d5
exd5 23. Nf1 Rxg2+ 24. Kxg2 dxc4 25. Kf2 Ne5 $19 {Black already has four pawns
for the rook and will soon attack with all his pieces. The next move could be .
..Re8 and ...Qh6, maybe with ...c7-c5 in between. The knight is active while
the bishop on b4 is completely out of play. Once again, we understand why the
exchange was premature.}) 22... Nxb4 $1 {Now is a good moment for this
exchange, weakening White's control over d4 and preparing the next pawn break.}
23. cxb4 f4 $1 24. exf4 (24. gxf4 Bxg2 25. Rxg2 Qh4+ {also wins}) 24... Qxd4+
25. Ke2 (25. Kf1 Qxa1+) 25... Bxg2 $19 {Black has won two pawns and his attack
continues. Or, if you love computer evaluations (I don't) it's a mate in 6.}) (
{Speaking about commitments, one may ask whether .. .Nxf2 is not a bit
committal, too. What if Black first brings his queen closer to the attacking
area with} 17... Qg5 $2 {The point is that the knight on e4 is exposed to
exchange, and the last move allows White to maintain approximate equality.} 18.
Nxe4 Qh5 19. h4 gxh3 20. Qe2 $1 (20. Kh2 $2 Nxb4 21. cxb4 Bxe4 {Threatening ...
Qf3, and if 22.Qe2 then 22...Bf3, winning the exchange.} 22. Bd3 Qf3 23. Bxe4
fxe4 24. Rg1 Rf8 $17) 20... h2+ 21. Kh1 fxe4 22. Qxh5 Rxh5 23. c5 $11) 18. cxb4
Qg5 $6 {Black continues the series of committal moves. The queen moves far
from the centre without creating serious threats.} ({It makes sense to
continue clearing the long diagonal with} 18... Nxd2 19. Rxd2 Be4 {, thus
avoiding the danger of the bishop being shut off with d4-d5.}) (18... Nxf2 {
was still playable, even though it would only lead to a perpetual:} 19. Kxf2
Rxh2+ 20. Kg1 Rh1+ 21. Kf2 $11 {The point is that} Qf6 $2 22. Bg2 Rh2 {runs
into} 23. d5 exd5 24. Nf1 $18 {In the absence of the queen's knight Black has
no compensation for the sacrificed material.}) 19. d5 $1 {[%csl Rb7]} Nxd2 $2 {
But now, exchanging the active knight does not make sense at all.} (19... Qh5
$5 20. h4 gxh3 21. Nxe4 fxe4 22. dxe6 (22. Qxe4 exd5 23. cxd5 Re8 $17 24. Qd3
$2 Qf3 $19) 22... d6 {Black has managed to establish some connection between
the opposite wings, allowing him to recycle the queen and rook. The position
would still be approximately equal.}) 20. Rxd2 Qh5 21. h4 gxh3 22. Kh2 d6 23.
a5 $16 {Black's attack has come to an end and his kingside major pieces are
too far from the opposite wing to allow parrying White's simple positional
attack. The bishop on b7 is both passive and vulnerable.} Qf3 24. axb6 axb6 25.
Ra7 Rg6 26. Qd1 (26. Rd4 Rg4 $1 $14) 26... Qg4 $6 (26... Qxd1 27. Rxd1 $16) 27.
Rd4 $6 ({Missing} 27. Qa4 $1 $18 {with the threat Rxb7} Kg7 28. Qd7+) 27... Qg5
$2 (27... Qxd1 $16) 28. Rh4 $18 {WHite stands better on both wings now.} Qf6
29. Bxh3 Qb2 30. Kg1 Ra8 $2 {A mistake in a desperate position.} 31. Rxa8+ ({
Only not} 31. Rxb7 Ra1) 31... Bxa8 32. Qa4 $18 Qc1+ {The bitter revenge check.}
(32... Bb7 33. Qe8+ Kg7 34. Qe7+ {[%csl Rg7]}) 33. Bf1 1-0

