{[%evp 0,84,16,13,30,-11,3,1,4,-25,-27,-4,30,24,41,36,45,41,70,46,69,73,39,22,
22,14,21,-30,-21,-28,-2,-8,-10,-33,-36,-36,-35,-35,-43,-38,-36,-58,-83,-107,
-86,-114,-73,-61,-59,-47,-52,-55,-68,-94,-95,-91,-72,-106,-72,-110,-101,-103,
-110,-110,-106,-140,-108,-138,-130,-152,-144,-147,-162,-181,-188,-283,-144,
-350,-341,-344,-344,-344,-354,-350,-370,-378,-365] There is a big difference
between the positions with two bishops against a bishop and a knight and those
resulting after the exchange of one bishop. This applies to the Nimzo-Indian
positions, too. Here are a few examples featuring a different line than above.
} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 Nc6 ({Until discovering the virtues of} 
4... b6 {, examined in my repertoire database, this was one of my favourite
systems.}) 5. Nf3 d6 6. Bd2 O-O 7. a3 Bxc3 8. Bxc3 a5 {This move not only
takes measures against b2-b4 but also starts the fight for the queenside light
squares. True, Black will never play ...a5-a4, preferring to keep this
positional threat in reserve. At this stage, developing is more important.} 9.
e3 Qe7 10. Bd3 e5 11. dxe5 {This looks like a small concession, but White had
two main ideas. Firstly, he removes the threat ...e5-e4. Secondly, he hopes to
open the diagonal for his dark-squared bishop.} dxe5 12. O-O {White's bishops
look threatening but the next move changes this impression.} Re8 {[%cal Ge5e4]
This simple move forces White to make a decision.} (12... e4 $2 13. Bxf6 $1)
13. Bf5 $6 {This plays into Black's hands. It provokes the exchange Black was
actually aiming for while also helping his development.} (13. Nd2 {is more
consistent, but Black would get good play on light squares anyway.} e4 14. Be2
Bf5 15. b3 h5 {[%cal Gf5g4]} 16. h3 Nd7 $11) 13... Bxf5 14. Qxf5 Qe6 {
Exchanging White's most advanced piece.} (14... a4 $5) 15. Qxe6 Rxe6 16. b4 $6
{The psychological threat of ...a5-a4 finally works. After the last move,
Black obtains a consistent advantage.} (16. Nd2 a4 {offers Black just very
comfortable play.}) 16... Ne4 17. Bb2 f6 $1 {The bishop turns very passive now.
In the presence of a white light-squared bishop, this might have been more
dangerous for Black.} 18. b5 Ne7 19. Rfd1 Rd6 $1 20. Kf1 (20. Rxd6 cxd6 {
turns c4 into chronic weakness.}) 20... Nc8 $1 {The knight is heading for b6.
Even though Black has placed his central pawns on dark squares, his main play
takes place on light squares. As mentioned above, his pawns only restrict the
enemy bishop, creating the feeling that Black is a piece up. On light squares,
he has the strong knight on e4 and a target on c4.} 21. Rdc1 (21. Ke2 Nb6 22.
Rac1 (22. Rxd6 cxd6 23. Rc1 Rc8 {Due to the strong knight on e4, White does
not have Nd2.}) 22... Rxd1 {In both lines, Black wins a pawn. In the last line,
the knight on e4 keeps f2 under attack.}) 21... c5 $5 (21... Nc5 $5 22. Ra2 Nb6
23. Ba1 Rad8 {was also strong. The bishop is so passive that the knights enjoy
stability on dark squares. However, we can understand that Keres did not wish
to remove the knight from e4.}) 22. Bc3 {Hoping to use the bishop for
defending f2 and d2.} (22. bxc6 Rxc6 {dooms the pawn on c4.}) 22... Nxc3 $1 {
Changing the course of the game. Black will get control over the d-file, so it
is useful to exchange the piece that could prevent the intrusion to d2.} 23.
Rxc3 e4 $1 {The other defender of the d2-square is pushed back. We can notice
that Keres will now place his central\ pawns on light squares since he does
not have anything to fear along the long diagonal.} 24. Ng1 Nb6 25. Ne2 f5 26.
Ke1 Rad8 27. Rc2 Kf7 28. Ng3 ({White cannot prevent the massive advance of the
black pawns:} 28. h4 Rh6 29. g3 g5 $1) 28... Ke6 29. Nf1 Rd3 30. Ng3 g5 31. Ne2
Na4 32. Ng3 Ke5 {Black's domination is decisive, but the invasion did not
reach its high peak yet.} 33. Nf1 h5 34. f3 Rb3 35. fxe4 fxe4 36. Rf2 Nb2 37.
Rc2 Nd3+ 38. Ke2 Rf8 39. Nd2 Rf2+ 40. Kd1 Rb2 41. Rxb2 Nxb2+ 42. Kc1 Rxg2 0-1

