{[%evp 0,72,16,13,16,-18,-5,-11,28,-10,-14,12,25,12,-1,8,24,32,23,25,47,34,48,
40,30,17,37,-48,-42,-33,20,15,2,-38,-34,-41,-34,-30,-32,-30,-23,-23,-13,-17,
-35,-27,-21,-32,-36,-42,-43,-56,-50,-66,-61,-52,-61,-68,-89,-140,-78,-53,-60,
-93,-46,-1029,-1082,-1144,-320,-1080,-604,-736,-883,-1894,-1924]} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 Nc6 5. Nf3 d6 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bd2 {I have never
understood why White sometimes provokes ...h7-h6. It looks like a useful move
to me.} O-O 8. a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Qe7 10. e3 a5 11. b3 e5 12. Be2 {Unlike in the
previous game, White did not release the central tension yet. He also placed
his king's bishop on a more modest, but safer square.} Bg4 {The light start of
the plan on light squares.} 13. O-O $6 {This yields Black easy play.} (13. d5 {
was more consistent, but this type of position belongs to the category "play
on dark squares".}) 13... e4 $1 {Starting to build up a massive control on
light suares.} 14. Ne1 Rfe8 (14... Bxe2 15. Qxe2 d5 {was simpler.}) 15. Bxg4
Nxg4 16. h3 ({White should have used the given chance to offer some breathing
space to his bishop.} 16. d5 $5 Nb8 17. h3 Nf6 {Black is doing fine, but White
is not in danger, either.}) 16... Nf6 17. Qd2 d5 $1 {White's bishop is more of
a spectator now, while the knight is not too active, either.} 18. Nc2 {This
allows Black to get global control over the light squares.} (18. a4 {looks
more logical. True, this would remove any chance for a queenside white
counterplay.} Qe6 19. Qe2 Ne7 20. Nc2 Nf5 {Dark clouds have gathered over the
white king's residence. I recommend comparing Black's queenside plan with that
from the classical game included in the database.}) 18... a4 {The thematical
move. White has to give up any control on d5.} (18... Qe6 {was also strong.})
19. Nb4 Nxb4 20. Bxb4 Qd7 21. bxa4 dxc4 22. Rac1 Rxa4 23. Rxc4 Nd5 {A typical
position with a dominating knight versus an ineffective bishop. The last move
also clears the rook's access from a4 to g6.} 24. Rfc1 Ra6 25. Qd1 Rg6 26. Qh5
{Desperately trying to keep Black's initiative under control.} Rg5 27. Qh4 Qf5
28. Ba5 c6 29. Rc5 Re6 {With the light squares firm in his hand, Black can
build his attack at leisure.} 30. Bd8 f6 $1 {Even though this deprives Black
from ...Reg6, it is the most consistent move. He needs to have heavy pieces on
g5 and g6.} 31. Rb1 Qg6 32. Rxb7 (32. g3 {allows Black to tend a network
around the white queen.} Qf7 33. a4 Re8 34. Ba5 h5 35. Bd2 Rf5 36. g4 Rg5)
32... Rxg2+ 33. Kf1 Rg5 (33... Rg1+ 34. Ke2 Qg2 $19) 34. a4 Qf5 35. Rb3 Qf3 {
[%cal Gf3d1]} 36. Rc1 (36. Ke1 Rg1+ 37. Kd2 Qd1# {[%cal Gd5c3]}) 36... Qh1+ 0-1

