{This game is of certain historic interest since it was played a couple of
days before Nimzowitsch used the opening bearing his name for the first time.
Before that, only very few games were played with it.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 b6 5. Bd3 Bb7 6. f3 c5 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 d5 9. Ne2 O-O 10. O-O
Nbd7 11. Ng3 Qc7 12. cxd5 exd5 {We have reached a familiar structure, but the
knight is better placed on g3 since it sustains e3-e4 and does not block the
f-pawn. Besides, Black's minor pieces are not optimally placed, preventing
Black to organise his counterplay.} 13. e4 $2 {A careless move.} ({White
should have still prepared the central break with} 13. Ra2 $1 {yielding him a
huge positional advantage.}) 13... cxd4 14. cxd4 Qc3 $1 15. Be3 dxe4 16. fxe4
Ba6 $5 {Undermining White's control over the important light square on e4.} ({
Tarrasch mentioned} 16... Bxe4 $5 {as an alternative. It also offers Black
good counterplay.} 17. Nxe4 Nxe4 {With two active bishops, White should have
reasonable compensation for the pawn, though.}) (16... Nc5 {was suggested
during the webinar and it looks quite OK, too.} 17. dxc5 (17. Rxf6 Nxd3 $1)
17... Rad8) 17. Bxa6 Qxe3+ 18. Kh1 Nxe4 19. Nf5 $1 {The only chance.} Nf2+ 20.
Rxf2 Qxf2 21. Qg4 g6 22. Rf1 Qb2 23. Nh6+ $2 (23. Ne7+ {, recommended by
Tarrasch was better.} Kg7 $1 (23... Kh8 24. Qxd7 Qxa3 (24... Rad8 25. Qh3 $16 {
Tarrasch}) 25. Bc8 Qd3 26. Rg1 Qc4 27. Qd6 $1 {Now is when the king stands
badly on h8.} Kg7 28. Bd7 $14 {Marin}) 24. Qxd7 Qxa3 25. Bc8 Qd3 $1 26. Rg1 (
26. Kg1 Qe3+ 27. Kh1 Qe6) 26... Qc4 {In both cases, the queenside pawns are a
permanent soure of worries for Black.}) 23... Kg7 24. Nxf7 Qb3 25. d5 Nf6 26.
Qd4 Rxf7 27. Bc4 Qa4 28. g4 Rc8 0-1

