{[%evp 0,78,19,31,25,-16,-12,-4,28,26,28,35,28,39,26,28,28,21,21,32,8,12,11,-8,
-7,12,7,10,32,16,33,-7,21,-55,-46,-95,-87,-78,-62,-54,-47,-68,-49,-59,-18,-42,
-2,-20,-15,5,1,1,1,-10,-15,-23,-14,-77,-89,-91,-87,-85,-77,-77,-67,-76,-68,
-102,-80,-89,-57,-55,-55,-61,-83,-73,-73,-65,-101,-120,-184]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3 c5 7. O-O Nc6 8. a3 Bxc3 9. bxc3 b6 $5
({The main lines are} 9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 Qc7) ({and} 9... Qc7 10. cxd5 exd5 {
True, in the latter case, the queen is not always optimally placed on c7.}) ({
The rare} 9... Re8 {may be a better way of delaying the queen's development
than the game move.}) 10. cxd5 exd5 {This game is an illustration of Black's
main dream in this structure.} 11. Nd2 $6 ({Theory considers that} 11. Ne5 {
is the best way of using the omission of ...Qc7.}) 11... Be6 12. Bb2 c4 13. Bc2
b5 14. f3 a5 15. Re1 (15. e4 Qb6 16. Kh1 b4 17. e5 Nd7 18. f4 f5) 15... Qb6 16.
Nf1 b4 17. Qd2 $2 (17. axb4 axb4 18. cxb4 Nxb4 19. Rxa8 Rxa8 20. Bc3 $15) 17...
b3 {Black has a huge queenside advantage and he only has to organise a
kingside blockade in order to reach a practically winning position.} 18. Bb1 a4
19. e4 Ne7 20. Ng3 Kh8 21. Re2 Nfg8 22. Nh5 f5 (22... dxe4 $5 23. Bxe4 (23.
fxe4 Bg4) 23... Ra5) 23. Qg5 Rf7 24. exf5 Bxf5 25. Bxf5 Nxf5 {White's
initiative has faded away and every new exchange makes his position more and
more difficult.} 26. Rae1 Qd8 27. Qxd8 Rxd8 28. Re8 $2 Rxe8 29. Rxe8 Re7 30.
Rxe7 Ngxe7 31. Kf2 Kg8 32. g4 Nd6 33. Ke3 Nb5 34. f4 Nc8 35. f5 Ncd6 36. Nf4 {
Apparently, White has reached certain activity... As in so many other cases,
Black's domination on light squares allows a blow on dark squares.} Nxa3 $1 (
36... Nxc3 $2 {was suggested during the webinar, but it does not work.} 37.
Bxc3 Nb5 38. Nxd5 ({Even better than} 38. Kd2 $18 {, which was my reaction
during the webinar.}) 38... Nxa3 39. Nb6 $18) 37. Bxa3 Nb5 38. Bc1 (38. Bb2 a3
39. Bxa3 Nxa3 40. Kd2 b2) 38... Nxc3 39. Ne2 (39. Kd2 Nb1+ 40. Kd1 a3 41. Bxa3
Nxa3 42. Nxd5 (42. Kc1 c3) 42... b2 43. Nc3 Kf7) 39... Nb1 0-1

