{[%evp 0,96,25,25,30,-4,5,0,26,28,28,24,26,28,32,19,27,11,17,17,53,7,20,-29,17,
-35,-15,-23,-24,-8,-9,-9,-6,-6,-6,3,9,5,0,-38,-25,-30,-28,-35,-25,-42,-17,-27,
-27,-23,-16,-18,5,-1,3,8,5,-15,-15,-26,-20,-16,-21,-45,-29,-30,-29,-29,-25,-31,
-23,-15,-22,-41,-21,-34,-46,-46,-9,-4,9,-23,-52,-65,-70,-70,-55,-63,-92,-83,
-74,-93,-134,-449,-449,-637,-528,-29989,-29990]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. O-O Nc6 8. a3 Bxc3 9. bxc3 Qc7 10. cxd5 exd5
11. Nh4 {According to Bagirov, this was the theory's last word. White prevents
the pin with ...Bg4 and clears the path for the f-pawn.} Ne7 12. Ra2 {A
typical way of bringing the rook into play. In some cases, it can sustain the
central break with Re2, in others it defends the king after a massive advance
of the kingside pawns.} Ng6 $1 {Provoking an exchange with long term
favourable consequences. The h-pawn will step closer to the centre, helping
Black in the fight against White's central expansion.} 13. Nxg6 ({White's
position would be hanging after} 13. Nf5 c4 14. Bb1 Ne4) 13... hxg6 14. f3 {
The position looks promising for White. he only needs to play Re2 followed by
Bb2 and e4 in order to get a crushing positional attack. And yet, it will take
another 23 moves before White will manage to put his centre into motion; by
then, it will be too late already...} Bf5 $1 {We can see a first positive
effect of ...hxg6. Black can immediately start fighting against e3-e4. White
cannot agree on exchanging the bishops, because this would leave him with too
many weaknesses on light squares.} 15. Be2 Rac8 16. g4 {There was no other way
to drive the molesting bishop away, but the g-pawn will be hanging now,
complicating the task of opening the centre.} Bd7 17. Rb2 b6 18. Ba6 {This
kind of moves usually provokes some lack of harmony in the enemy camp. During
the next few moves, Sokolov's pieces will follow similar trajectories as in
the Benjamin game, leading to a complete restoring of the coordination.} Rce8
19. Bd3 Qc6 20. Rg2 Re7 21. Qd2 Rc8 22. Bb2 Qa4 23. Re1 {Once again, White
seems close to his goal: if given the time, he would play h3 and e4, with a
clear advantage. However, Black's guerilla continues to keep him busy on the
opposite wing.} Bb5 24. Bc2 Qc4 25. Qd1 {Intending to expel the enemy queen
with Bb3.} (25. e4 $2 {would lose a pawn in an amusing way:} dxe4 26. fxe4 Nxe4
$1 {since the rook has to parry ...Qf1 mate!}) 25... cxd4 $5 {So far, Sokolov
has played a mainly defensive game, but his last move marks the start of a new
phase. By opening the c-file, he declares his intentions to take over the
initiative on the queenside.} ({As pointed out by Bagirov,} 25... Rce8 {
was entirely possible, since} 26. Bb3 Qd3 27. Rd2 $2 {would be bad on account
of} Rxe3 $1) 26. cxd4 Rec7 27. Bb3 {White has to deviate from his main
temporarily in order to keep his bishops' pair.} ({After} 27. Bb1 Ba4 {
followed by ...Bc2 soon, Black would not have any problems.}) 27... Qc6 28. Qd2
Ba4 {Starting a new wave of harassment.} 29. Ba2 Qb5 30. Qb4 Qd7 31. Bb1 {
Still hoping to get e4-going...} Bc2 $1 {But Black's regrouping is too strong
to allow that.} 32. Bxc2 ({White cannot avoid the exchange under favourable
circumstances anymore:} 32. Ba2 a5 33. Qd2 Qb5 34. Ba1 ({Bagirov analyses only
} 34. Bc1 {Bb1, which is nice for Black, indeed. However, even stronger would
be:} Ne4 $3 35. fxe4 Bxe4 {, winning material.}) 34... g5 $5 {With the enemy
bishop trapped on a1, this move does not suppose any risk. The enemy centre is
kept under observation, and the g6-square has become available for the bishop,
in order to allow the continuation of the attack on the c-file.}) 32... Rxc2
33. Ree2 Rxe2 34. Rxe2 Rc4 35. Qe1 a5 36. h3 {The last exchanges have largely
favoured Black, but White will finally play e4. Unfortunately for him, Black
will manage to block the enemy centre rather easily.} Ne8 $1 {The knight is
heading for e6. In principle, the weakness of the f4-square, provoked by the
inevitable e3-e4, should not be chronical as long as there is a dark-squared
bishop on board, but concretely this is how things will be. Given Black's
authoritarian control over the c-file and the weakness of the d4-pawn, White
will never get to regroup with Bc1-e3, in order to cover all the weaknesses.}
37. e4 {Passive policy would not guarantee safety. Black would put his knight
on e6 anyway, and then prepare the advance of his queenside majority.} Nc7 38.
Qg3 Rc6 $1 {Defending b6 in order to enable ...Ne6.} 39. h4 Ne6 {White's
structure has become similar to Kortschnoj's shortly before the time control.
There are no concrete white threats, though, while the white king risks
becoming as vulnerable as in the previous game.} 40. exd5 $6 {An impulsive
move right before the control. Jussupow probably hoped to put his d-pawn into
motion, but his positional judgement in time trouble proved wrong.} ({The
another way of releasing the tension would not be good, either:} 40. e5 $6 Rc4
41. Rd2 Qa4 42. Qf2 Qb3 43. Kg2 ({Somewhat better than} 43. f4 $2 Qh3 {as
analyzed by Bagirov.}) 43... g5 $5 44. hxg5 Nxg5 {White has no obvious plan of
advancing his majority without allowing the knight to e4, while the queenside
pawns are ready to march in.}) ({White should have overdefended his d4-pawn
with} 40. Rd2 $5 {maintaining hopes for successful defence.}) 40... Qxd5 41.
Re5 Qd6 {This move was sealed.} ({According to Bagirov, most of the
commentators were expecting} 41... Qb3 {, with the possible continuation:} 42.
d5 Rc2 43. dxe6 Qxb2 44. e7 Rg2+ $1 45. Qxg2 Qxe5 46. Qb2 Qxe7 47. Qxb6 Qxa3 {
. I like Sokolov's move better. The queen ending still offers technical
difficulties, while in the middlegame Black maintains a strong attack.}) 42.
Qh2 ({The point is that after} 42. d5 Rc2 43. dxe6 fxe6 {the bishop is lost
and the white king is in deadly danger.}) 42... Qc7 43. Re2 Nf4 {The start of
the decisive attack.} 44. Re4 f5 $1 {An elegant way of ensuring the knight's
stability.} 45. Re8+ ({After} 45. Rxf4 Rc2 46. Qg3 Rxb2 {White can avoid (or
rather delay) mate only at the cost of huge material losses.}) 45... Kf7 46.
Ra8 Re6 47. Qd2 Re2 48. Qc3 Nh3+ 0-1

