{[%evp 0,34,25,20,37,-9,-7,4,23,-35,11,-59,-37,-55,-27,-60,-25,-31,3,-7,-5,-17,
0,-19,-6,-21,-32,-24,-7,-10,-33,-7,-24,-79,-79,-186,-77]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 {This line is sometimes referred to as the Leningrad or Spassky
Variation in the Nimzo-Indian. Although it is a little out of fashion, it has
been featured in games of strong players such as Ivanchuk, Jussupow, Onischuk
and others.} h6 {The idea is to force White to make a decision- either give up
the bishop or play Bh4 and give up the possibility to protect the queenside.
It is hard to imagine that White would be able to pose serious problems after
Bxf6 so I would focus primarily on Bh4.} 5. Bh4 (5. Bxf6 Qxf6 6. e3 {White
tries to transpose to Ragozin but we can just reply with c5 and get a
comfortable position} c5 $11) 5... c5 6. d5 {The critical continuation} (6. Nf3
$6 {allows Black to take over the initiative} g5 $1 7. Bg3 g4 8. Ne5 Ne4 $1 9.
Qd3 Qa5 {winning a pawn} 10. Rc1 Qxa2 $17 {0-1 (32) Mondy,M (1889)-Ellis,M
ICCF email 2011} 11. Qxe4 $4 Qxb2 $19 12. Qc2 Qxc2 13. Rxc2 cxd4 {regaining
the material with interest}) (6. e3 {A possible move, although no strong
players have tried it. We retain the possibility to play Qa5 and Ne4 in the
next moves} Nc6) 6... d6 7. e3 {Most natural since White needs to complete his
development} Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 {We get the typical Nimzo-Indian middlegame: White
gets the bishop pair at the expense of long-term weaknesses c3 and c4. However,
in this particular line, I believe White does not get sufficient compensation
for his wrecked pawn structure on the queenside as Black's position is very
solid} e5 {There are a couple of options White can try:} 9. Bd3 (9. f3 e4 $1 {
Consistent with Black's strategic plans- we do not allow the opponent to
comfortably get e4} 10. f4 (10. fxe4 $6 g5 11. Bg3 (11. e5 gxh4 12. exf6 Qxf6
$17 {[%cal Yb8d7,Yd7e5,Ye8e4] with clear positional advantage due to White's
many weaknesses}) 11... Nxe4 $17) 10... g5 $1 {Getting rid of the pin by
exploiting the fact that Bh4 is unprotected} 11. Bg3 {The logical continuation
as taking the pawn is far too risky} (11. fxg5 Ng4 12. Nh3 Qe7 $17 {[%csl Ge3]
[%cal Gg4e5]}) 11... Qe7 12. Be2 {[%csl Rg1] White has problems with his
kingside development} gxf4 13. Bxf4 Rg8 $146 (13... Nbd7 {also works} 14. Nh3
Ne5 15. Nf2 Ng6 16. Bg3 (16. O-O $1 {is necessary but practically unpleasant}
Nxf4 17. exf4 Bd7 $15 {[%cal Ge8c8]}) 16... h5 $36 {looks very suspicious for
White. The advance of the h5 pawn is rather unpleasant}) 14. g3 Kd8 $44 {
The king is in a safe position due to the closed centre and now Black can
start playing aggressively by exchanging the light-squared bishops (via g4)
and then proceeding with occupying e5 and d3 with the knights}) (9. Qc2 {
The goal of this move is to prevent Bf5} g5 $1 {restricting Bh4 and gaining
space} 10. Bg3 Qe7 11. Nf3 (11. e4 Nbd7 {completing development} (11... Nh5 {
is also possible. The idea is to follow up with f5 at some later point in the
game (we do not wish to exchange Bg3)}) 12. f3 Nf8 13. Bf2 Ng6 14. g3 Bd7 $15 {
[%cal Ge8c8,Gh6h5,Gg5g4] Black's play comes naturally while it is difficult to
suggest how White can generate threats in the near future}) 11... e4 {gaining
more space} 12. Nd2 Bf5 13. Rb1 (13. h4 O-O $1 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7e5,Gf5g6,Gg8g7]
I believed the most played Rg8 gave up the line without need so I settled on
this move instead}) (13. Be2 Nbd7 14. Rb1 b6 15. O-O O-O {The king is safe on
the kingside since White has also castled short and h4 is rarely a threat.
White's main idea is to push a5 but in fact, this would not bring him much.
Meanwhile, Black can follow up with Re8, Ne5, Nd3 .} 16. a4 Bg6 $17 {0-1 (77)
Kretov,E (2138) -Lysyj,I (2527) Internet 2006}) 13... O-O 14. h4 (14. Be2 {
transposes to the Spassky game} Bg6 15. h4 b6 $17 {ctr f7}) (14. f4 {An
interesting tactical possibility. Unfortunately for White, Black is able to
take over after} Ng4 $1 $17 15. Ke2 {only move but not enough to keep the
position balanced} gxf4 16. Bxf4 Nd7 {Black needs to play aggressively and not
lose any tempi. The initiative more than compensates for the pawn} 17. Rxb7 $6
Rfb8 18. Rxb8+ Rxb8 $40 19. h3 {Ke2 is problematic and White is still yet to
develop his pieces} Nge5 {[%cal Ye5d3,Yb8b2] The knight aims for d3}) 14... Bg6
{[%cal Gd7e5] A very important prophylactic move which ensures that the bishop
would not be hanging any longer (the e4 pawn is not pinned)} 15. Be2 b6 16. Kd1
Nbd7 17. Kc1 Kg7 18. Kb2 {Even though White won, he should be clearly worse
after: 1-0 (41) Spassky,B (2580) -Brunner,L (2505) Germany 1989} Ne5 $146 {
[%cal Ge5d3,Gb6b5]}) (9. Nf3 $6 {allows Black to develop the bishop on a
preferable square} Bf5 10. Nd2 {Typical manoeuvre- White dreams of achieving
f3, e4 structure and enjoy the advantage of the bishop pair} (10. Be2 g5 {
The position is closed so Black can afford to play g5 and thus gain excellent
play restricting Bh4. As a reminder, whenever we push g5 we have to be mindful
of a potential h4 break. Next moves are going to be Nbd7, Qe7, e4 etc} 11. Bg3
Nbd7 $15) 10... Nbd7 {a more flexible choice} ({although} 10... g5 {is fine too
} 11. Bg3 Qe7 (11... Nbd7 12. f3) 12. Be2 $15) 11. e4 (11. f3 e4 {Once again
we cannot allow White to push e4 and get a comfortable position.} 12. fxe4 {
Black receives a great compensation for the pawn as White has too many
weaknesses} g5 13. exf5 gxh4 {The semi-open e and g files combined with
White's crippled pawn structure ensure that Black has the advantage. He is
going to obtain great squares for his pieces after Qe7, 0-0-0, Rg8, Ne5 and
then further exploit the gaps in White's position}) 11... g5 $146 (11... Bh7
12. f3 $14 {1/2-1/2 (27) Gabriel,C (2562)-Socko,B (2569) Germany 2003}) 12.
exf5 gxh4 13. Bd3 Ke7 {There is no reason to castle as the Black king is
perfectly safe in the centre. This slightly unusual move opens up the way for
the Black queen and Ra8 to swing over to the kingside via the g file. Moreover,
c3 and c4 continue to be long-term weaknesses and h4 can create additional
trouble for White} 14. O-O Qg8 $15) 9... e4 {Going for e4 whenever possible as
such transformation of the structure favours Black} 10. Bc2 (10. Bxe4 {fails to
} g5) 10... Nbd7 11. Ne2 (11. f4 Nb6 $1 {Targetting c4} 12. Qe2 Bg4 {
developing with a tempo} 13. Qf1 (13. Bxf6 Qxf6 {[%cal Yf6c3]}) 13... g5 $1 {
the already familiar idea} 14. fxg5 Nh5 15. a4 hxg5 16. Bf2 {[%cal Yd8f6,Yf6c3,
Ye8c8] 1/ 2-1/2 (36) Ivanchuk, V (2717) -Topalov, V (2718) Wijk aan Zee 2001
Even though the game fizzled out in a draw, Black has a very pleasant position}
Qf6 17. Ra3 O-O-O $17 {with solid long-lasting advantage}) 11... Qe7 {Not
rushung with g5 and Ne5} 12. Qb1 {aiming at the e4 pawn delaying the castling}
(12. O-O $2 {is bad as White comes under a crushing attack} g5 $19 13. Bg3 h5
14. h4 Nh7 {with very one-sided game} 15. Qb1 gxh4 16. Bf4 Ng5 17. Bxg5 Qxg5
18. Nf4 Nf6 19. Kh2 h3 20. gxh3 Bxh3 21. Rg1 (21. Nxh3 Ng4+ $19) 21... Ng4+ 22.
Kxh3 Nxf2+ 23. Kh2 Qh4+ 24. Kg2 Rg8+ {0-1 (24) Bredenhof,B (2215) -Schaefer,U 
(2226) ICCF email 2010}) 12... O-O 13. O-O g5 14. Bg3 Nb6 $146 {[%cal Yb6c4]
Black does not have any weaknesses and all his pieces are on active squares}
15. Qb3 Bg4 {A subtle move provoking Rae1 so that after Bd7, a4 is not
possible. Rfe1 does not help White either as it contradicts his plan of
undermining e4 with f3} 16. Rae1 Bd7 $19 17. Bb1 Nh5 $36 *

