{[%evp 0,65,19,31,14,-14,-11,4,33,31,35,1,35,-6,-9,4,-10,-47,22,17,33,9,34,22,
35,27,21,26,-7,9,-4,-2,-2,-17,-17,-17,-17,5,-7,-6,-13,-17,-19,-15,-17,-15,-3,
-11,-8,-3,-7,-10,-5,-15,-8,0,0,0,8,0,7,0,5,5,5,0,5,1]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 {Black has a wide choice of systems to choose from: for example,
reputable authors such as GMs Marin and Kuljasevic suggest 4...b6 in their
repertoire for Modern Chess while GM Roiz prefers 4...c5. Personally, I
decided to settle on 4...0-0 as after 4...c5 I was concerned that after 5.g3
White's position is very solid while Black needs to be more careful.
Additionally, the position may transpose to the more popular 4.Qc2 or 4.e3
lines where 0-0 is the main move} O-O 5. Bg5 (5. g3 Bxc3+ {I encountered this
move while preparing my analysis and to my surprise, I was quite satisfied
with the arising positions. It is such a natural solution- after all, we play
the Nimzo to give up the bishop!} ({Previously, I liked} 5... d5 {as a
solution but Iater I found the 5...Bxc3 which suited better my style.} 6. Bg2
dxc4 7. O-O Nc6 8. Qa4 {There is rich play for both sides here so I have
suggested this line to some of my students. Black has enough resources to
counter White's threats so the variation remains very playable.}) 6. bxc3 b6 {
[%csl Yc4]} 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. O-O {Here, I ultimately decided on} d6 (8... h6 $5 {
is a good option, too. However, later I thought- why lose a tempo for h6? If
White wants to give up his bishop, he is free to do so!}) 9. a4 {The top
played move. White simply awaits Black's reaction} (9. Re1 h6 {we defer the
development of Nb8 a little so we can decide whether to put it on d7 or c6} 10.
Bf1 {White moves Bg2 so that when he moves Nf3 there is no trade of Bishops} (
10. Bh3 Re8 ({or} 10... Ne4 $5 {[%cal Yf7f5] with similar to Queen's Indian
Defence play}) 11. Qc2 $6 e5 12. Nd2 {1/2-1/2 (50) Suleymanli,A (2535)-Muradli,
M (2449) Nakhchivan 2021} e4 $1 $17 {[%csl Gc4] Preventing e4 once again})
10... Re8 {preparing e5} 11. a4 a5 $5 {Usually, we do not reply when White
pushes a4, but Grischuk decided to do so anyway. The move is a little risky
since if White manages to push c5, there would be too many weak squares on the
queenside. A favourable factor for Black though is the position of Bf1- it
allows for an easier jump Ne4} 12. Nh4 e5 13. dxe5 (13. d5 {is rarely in
White's favor as it surrenders control over the center} e4 $1 $17 {[%csl Yg5]
[%cal Yb8d7] Black is strategically better. White does not have the means to
develop an attack since even Bg5 is not possible}) 13... dxe5 {with a
favorable position} 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 $17 {0-1 (52) Harikrishna,P (2680) -Grischuk,
A (2719) Foros 2006}) (9. c5 {is always a move we need to consider because it
transforms the pawn structure. As a general rule, taking the pawn is not
advisable since White gets a lot of active play after Ba3 etc.} dxc5 10. dxc5
Qc8 $146 {Keeping the queens on board and clearing the d8 square for the rook}
11. c4 Rd8 12. Qc2 Nbd7 13. cxb6 axb6 $15 {Even though White got rid of his
doubled pawns, he did not solve all of his problems. The queenside is still
vulnerable with a2 and c4 subjects to a potential attack}) (9. Bg5 Nbd7 {
I want to have Nf6} (9... h6 {is another reliable choice which leads to a
different type of position} 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Qd3 Re8 {White achieved his goal
of pushing e4 by giving up the dark-squared bishop for Nf6} 12. e4 {A good
model game is: 0-1 (43) Li,C (2757) -Fedoseev,V (2664) Karlsruhe 2016} Nc6 {
trying to provoke d5} (12... e5 {I do not want to rush with this move since 13.
Nh4 followed by f4 might prove to be dangerous in the future. Because of that,
I thought it is better to prepare it first with 12...Nc6 instead. What is more,
by using this move order we keep c5 as an option too}) 13. Nd2 $140 (13. Rad1
Rad8 $44 {Improving our pieces while we continue waiting for White to make his
intentions clear. Black's position is good but nonetheless, I lean more
towards 9.Nbd7}) 13... e5 {Now once the knight is away from f3 we play 13...e5
and challenge the centre} 14. d5 Nb8 $17 {[%cal Yb8d7,Yd7c5]}) 10. Nd2 {
Exchanging the light-squared bishops so that pushing e4 is possible} Bxg2 11.
Kxg2 h6 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. e4 c5 $13 {[%cal Yc5d4,Ya8c8,Yf6d7] is a fresh move
that is highly logical. The resulting position is dynamic and with lots of
possibilities.} (13... e5 {has been tried in tournament practice. However, I
was concerned that White has some play along the f-file} 14. f4 Re8 15. Qf3 a6
$146 {[%cal Gb6b5] Here I consider going for the pawn break of b5 the best
option- we give up targetting the weak pawn on c4 but crate enough counterplay
on the side.})) (9. d5 {is out of fashion now but still needs to be checked.}
Nbd7 {Just finishing development} (9... exd5 $2 {White uses an idea from
Queen's Indian Defence- if we take on d5, he is going to jump Nh4 and
recapture the pawn with a better position. Even if Black defends the pawn,
White gets excellent counterplay achieving an open position with two active
bishops and an excellent f5 square for Nf3.} 10. Nh4 $16 c6 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12.
Nf5 $40) 10. Nd4 (10. Bg5 h6 $1 {forcing White to exchange the bishop} 11. Bxf6
Qxf6 12. Nd4 e5 $1 $146 13. Nb3 Ba6 $17 {with long-term advantage due to
White's weak pawns}) (10. dxe6 {is not dangerous for Black} fxe6 $15 11. Ng5
Bxg2 12. Nxe6 Qe7 13. Nxf8 Bxf1 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 {[%cal Yf6e4,Ya8f8,Yf6g4] too
many weaknesses} 15. Kxf1 (15. Qxf1 $6 Qe6 $17) 15... Re8 16. f3 {[%csl Ye8]
trying to cover g4} Re5 {[%cal Ye5c5,Ye5h5,Yd7h3,Yf3g4,Yf3e4] with great
attacking chances}) 10... e5 {very natural and strong} 11. Nf5 (11. Nc6 {
is nothing to worry about} Qe8 $17) 11... Nc5 12. e4 Bc8 {[%csl Ye4][%cal
Yc8f5] A very important move: Black cannot tolerate the powerful Nf5 as it
poses a direct threat on the king} 13. Qe2 Bxf5 {[%cal Ye5e4,Yc5d3,Yf6d7,Yd7e5]
Changing the structure and aiming for e4} 14. exf5 {1/2-1/2 (27) Mulyar,M  
(2382) -Margvelashvili,G (2565) Philadelphia 2013} Re8 {[%cal Ge5e4]} 15. Be3
e4 $15) 9... Nc6 {[%cal Yc6a5] heading to a5 and targeting c4} (9... h6 {
is one possibility} 10. Re1 (10. a5 Qc8 $11)) ({I believe} 9... a5 $6 {to be a
little dubious since it gives more strength to the c5 break}) 10. Nd2 (10. Ba3
{[%cal Yc4c5]} Na5 11. Nd2 (11. c5 Nc4 $17 {Now if White chooses to take on d6/
b6, he would still have problems along the c file}) 11... Bxg2 12. Kxg2 c5 $1 {
Shutting down the bishop and threatening to open the c file in the future} 13.
e4 Rc8 14. d5 Re8 15. Qf3 Rc7 {Swinging the rook along the 7th rank} 16. Qd3
Rce7 $17 {[%cal Yc8a6,Yf6d7,Yd8c8,Ye6d5] White is very passive and Black is
sure to take over 0-1 (35) Koziej,M (2022)-Hracek,Z (2631) Trzcianka 2015})
10... Na5 11. e4 (11. Bxb7 {The Bishop pair does not make a great difference
here because the position is closed.} Nxb7 12. e4 (12. Nb3 {Trying to prevent
Na5. Sadly for him, this does not ease his position:} d5 13. cxd5 exd5 $15 {
Taking of the advantage that the bishops are swapped and the white squares are
weakened}) 12... e5 13. f4 {seems very aggressive and is for sure White's best
bet. Black should react by putting pressure with Re8} (13. Re1 Re8 14. f3 Na5 {
[%cal Yc7c6,Yd6d5] Black managed to play Na5 before White could prevent it
with Nb3. All the White pieces are tied to protect the central pawns} 15. Rb1
Qd7 $17 {1/2-1/2 (56) Terry,R (2514) -Lenderman,A (2648) chess24.com INT 2019})
13... Re8 14. Qf3 Na5 $1 $146 (14... c5 $6 {Is an interesting choice but I
think that White has some attacking chances here} 15. d5 exf4 16. gxf4 Na5 17.
Bb2 Nd7 18. Rae1 $13 {1-0 (37) Khurtsidze,N (2455)-Vakhania,A (2145) Tbilisi
2015}) 15. g4 {[%cal Yd8d7,Yd7c6] I considered it necessary to check this move
as it is always intimidating to play with a pawn storm against our king. There
is no other way for White to untangle} exf4 16. g5 Nd7 17. Qxf4 f6 $15 {
A complicated position for sure but according to the computer Black is a bit
better.}) 11... c5 {I find this structure to be more preferable over the
positions after e5} (11... e5 12. Re1 Re8 13. Ba3 $13) 12. Re1 {[%cal Ya8c8]}
h6 $146 {waiting move} (12... e5 $2 13. d5 {would favour White since he has
chances for kingside play. What is more, the bishop pair allows him to easily
protect his weaknesses meanhile}) 13. d5 {the consequences of pushing d5
should always be considered. We follow up with the natural setup Qe7, Re8
keeping the tension. Over the next moves, we prepare exd5 at a suitable moment
and attack c4. Another factor in Black's favour is that Bc1 is out of play and
heavily restricted} Qd7 $15) 5... c5 6. Rc1 (6. e3 {does not promise White any
advantage either} cxd4 7. exd4 d5 8. Rc1 Nc6 (8... Be7 $5) 9. a3 (9. Bd3 dxc4
10. Bxc4 b6 $11 {achieving a good version an Isolated Queen's Pawn} 11. O-O Bb7
12. a3 Be7 13. Qd3 h6 14. Bh4 Nh5 15. Bg3 Nxg3 16. hxg3 Bf6 {Black has
effortlessly solved his opening problems and starts improving the position of
his pieces} 17. Rfd1 Ne7 {[%cal Yd8d6,Ya8c8] 0-1 (38) Wang,H (2725)-Ganguly,S 
(2638) Changsha 2019}) 9... Bxc3+ 10. Rxc3 Re8 11. Be2 (11. Ne5 dxc4 {1-0 (40)
Kostyra,S (2270)-Rusak, J (1482) Bialystok 2013} 12. Nxc6 (12. Bxf6 $2) 12...
bxc6 13. Bxc4 h6 14. Bh4 e5 $11) 11... h6 12. Bh4 dxc4 13. Bxc4 (13. O-O b5 14.
b3 $6 Qa5 15. b4 $4 Qd8 $19 {0-1 (21) Lupulescu,C (2626)-Lysyj,I (2671) Baku
2015}) 13... e5 {with easy equality} 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. O-O Qxd1 16. Rxd1 Nxf3+
17. gxf3 g5 18. Bg3 Bh3 $11) 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 h6 (7... e5 $5 {a rare move
that directly fights for the initiative} 8. Ndb5 d5 9. cxd5 a6 10. Bxf6 (10.
Na3 {saw White rapidly getting into an unpleasant position} Qxd5 11. Bxf6 Qxd1+
12. Kxd1 gxf6 13. Nc4 $6 Rd8+ 14. Kc2 Nc6 $36 {0-1 (44) Edouard,R (2611)-Vidit,
S (2726) Tornelo INT 2021}) 10... Qxf6 11. Qa4 (11. Nc7 $5 {leads to an
unbalanced game} Ra7 12. a3 Ba5 13. d6 Rd8 $13) (11. Na3 Nd7 12. g3 (12. e3 Qg6
$1 $15) 12... Bc5 13. e3 Qh6 14. Bg2 b5 $44) 11... Qh4 (11... Bd7 $5 12. Qxb4
axb5 $14 {[%cal Gb8a6]}) (11... Qh6 12. e3 Bc5 $44) 12. a3 Qh6 13. Rd1 Bc5 14.
Ne4 Bb6 15. Nbd6 Bxf2+ 16. Nxf2 Qxd6 17. e4 Nd7 18. Qc2 Nf6 19. Be2 Bd7 20. O-O
Rfc8 21. Qb3 Qc5 22. Rc1 Qa7 23. Kh1 Rxc1 {0-1 (23) Saule,Z (1762) -Brusila,H 
(2216) ICCF email 2008}) 8. Bh4 Be7 {A more positional continuation which
avoids the forced lines after 8...d5} (8... d5 {ensures massive complications}
9. cxd5 g5 (9... e5) 10. Bg3 Qxd5 11. e3 Qxa2 12. Bd3 (12. Qc2 {1-0 (33)
Carlsen,M (2863)-So,W (2770) chess24.com INT 2020}) 12... Qxb2 13. O-O Bxc3 14.
Rc2 Qb4 15. Nb5 $44 {1-0 (61) Mamedyarov,S (2770)-Nakamura,H (2736) chess24.
com INT 2021}) 9. e3 (9. e4 Nxe4) 9... Nc6 10. Be2 Qb6 $1 {Posing concrete
problems to the opponent: the queen goes to an active position meanwhile
making room for Rd8 and preparing d5.} 11. Qd2 (11. O-O Qxb2 {accepting the
challenge} 12. Ndb5 Qb4 13. Bg3 d6 $146 {Black returns the extra material in
order to activate his pieces} (13... Qa5) (13... Ne8 {0-1 (48) Karthik,V (2305)
-Gagare,S (2486) Bhubaneswar 2016} 14. Ne4) 14. Bxd6 Bxd6 15. Qxd6 Rd8 16. Qxb4
Nxb4 $11) (11. Ndb5 a6) 11... d5 12. cxd5 Nxd4 13. exd4 exd5 (13... Ne4 $5 14.
Nxe4 Bxh4 $44) 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nxd5 Qxd4 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 17. O-O Be6 18. Bf3
Rad8 19. Qa5 Qxb2 20. Qxa7 b5 21. a4 bxa4 22. Qxa4 Qd4 23. Qxd4 Rxd4 24. Rfd1
Rfd8 25. Rxd4 Rxd4 26. Rd1 Rxd1+ 27. Bxd1 g5 28. g3 Bd5 29. Be2 Be6 30. Bd1 Bd5
31. Be2 Be6 32. Bd1 Bd5 33. Be2 {1/2-1/2 (33) Mamedyarov,S (2782)-Le,Q (2709)
Saint Louis 2021} *

