{[%evp 0,40,39,31,28,-14,0,-11,33,-31,-19,-6,-11,8,29,63,78,13,17,4,8,8,65,28,
33,35,138,61,108,108,82,73,34,0,20,0,20,-6,0,6,3,-19,3]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {The 4.f3 system is considered to be one of the most reliable
weapons against the Nimzo-Indian. It is frequently featured in top-GM games
and is definitely a must-know if you choose to add 3. Bb4 to your repertoire}
c5 {is my preferred system of choice as it typically results in very dynamic
play} (4... d5 {is the other main line which may go:} 5. a3 Be7 6. e4 dxe4 ({
Recently, I also came across} 6... dxc4 $5 {which I think is worth analyzing}
7. Be3 b5 8. Nxb5 Ba6 $11 {0-1 (42) Wojtaszek,R (2705)-Esipenko,A (2677) Wijk
aan Zee 2021}) 7. fxe4 e5 {and so on}) 5. d5 (5. a3 {has been tried by current
World Champion Magnus Carlsen therefore I decided to give it a check as well:}
Bxc3+ (5... Ba5 $5 {is another possible alternative since 6.bxc5 would fail to
6...Bxc3 where White's pawn structure is completely demolished}) 6. bxc3 d6 7.
e4 Nc6 8. Ne2 b6 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Yc6a5,Yc8a6] Black gets the typical play
against the c4 pawn. Moreover, moving the pawn to a3 appears to have been a
loss of a tempo- it even blocks the a3 square for Bc1} 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 O-O
11. Nc1 Ba6 12. Nb3 Rc8 {[%cal Yc8c4]} 13. Be2 cxd4 14. cxd4 {1/2-1/2 (23)
Ljubicic,A  (2465)-Fischer,W (2445) ICCF email 2017} Ne7 $5 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16.
Rc1 Ng6 $15 {with great position}) 5... O-O 6. e4 b5 $5 {Black immediately
puts pressure on White's centre with this bold move. This very interesting
line has been on the rise since a couple of famous authors recommended it in
their work. The fact that World number 2 Fabiano Caruana won a complicated
game against Shakhriyar Mamedyarov in the recent Sinquefield Cup only adds to
its current popularity} 7. e5 (7. Nh3 {has been tested by a number of
grandmasters among whom star junior Alireza Firouzja} bxc4 8. Bxc4 Nxd5 $5 {
[%cal Yd8h4,Yh4c4] A rather fancy move setting up a small trap:} (8... exd5 9.
Bxd5 Nxd5 10. Qxd5 {is a transposition}) 9. Bxd5 (9. exd5 $2 Qh4+ $1 {[%csl
Gc4]}) 9... exd5 10. Qxd5 Ba6 $1 {is a better choice than 10...Nc6 in my
opinion} (10... Nc6 $6 {has been played in a game between top players but I
did not like the position that could arise after:} 11. O-O (11. Be3 $6 Ba6 12.
Nf4 Qh4+ $17 13. g3 {The queen maneuver provoked weakening of the flank and
made f3 a potential target} Qf6 $40 {0-1 (52) Radjabov,T (2765)-So,W (2770)
chess24. com INT 2021}) 11... Ba6 {I believe White is slightly better} 12. Rd1
Nd4 13. Kh1 $14) 11. Bf4 (11. Bg5 {has also been tried} Qb6 12. Kf2 Nc6 13.
Rhd1 Ba5 {Opening the path to b2 and freeing the b4 square for Nc6} 14. Na4 $2
(14. Rab1 Rab8 $13) 14... Qb5 15. b3 $17 {0-1 (59) Lysenko, M (2290) -Guichard,
P (2408) Moscow 2019} Rae8 $36 {[%cal Ge8e5]}) ({The key point is that} 11.
Qxa8 $4 {runs into} Qh4+ $1 12. Nf2 (12. g3 Qxh3 $19) 12... Nc6 $19 {and the
queen is trapped. Even though White has two rooks for the queen, he cannot
complete his development and is utterly lost}) 11... Nc6 {[%cal Yb4e1,Ya6f1]}
12. Kf2 {Trying to solve the problem of the king} Ba5 {[%cal Gc6b4,Ya5b6]} 13.
Rhd1 Nb4 14. Qd6 (14. Qxd7 Nd3+ $17) 14... Bb6 15. Kg1 Nd3 {Although
complicated, Black's position is tactically sound and he has nothing to be
afraid of.} 16. Na4 {is probably best and leads to an equal game} (16. Bg5 $2
c4+ 17. Kh1 {0-1 (24) Tsvetkov,A (2358)-Sonis,F  (2490) Lichess.org INT 2020}
Qc7 $17) 16... c4+ 17. Nxb6 (17. Kh1 $6 {1/2-1/2  (60) Gazis, E (2146)
-Alexakis,D (2450) Aghios Kirykos 2021} Rc8 18. Nxb6 Qxb6 19. Qxb6 axb6 $15 {
seems preferable for Black because of the strong outpost on d3}) 17... Qxb6+
18. Qxb6 axb6 $11) (7. Bd2 {is another natural continuation} bxc4 8. Bxc4 Ba6 (
8... exd5 9. Nxd5 Ba6 {is objectively good as well}) 9. Bxa6 (9. b3 $6 {
White cannot maintain proper control of the central squares} exd5 10. exd5 Bxc4
11. bxc4 d6 12. Nge2 Nbd7 $15) 9... Nxa6 10. Nge2 c4 11. O-O Nc5 {Here, the
computer gives his notorious evaluation 0.00 but I tend to disagree- in
practice, it is much more pleasant to play from Black's side} 12. Nf4 e5 13.
Nh3 {0-1 (51) Bobkov,V (2346) -Lintchevski,D (2555) Novorossiysk 2021} Rb8 $15)
(7. cxb5 $2 {needs to be checked as well} exd5 8. exd5 {we get to a Benko
Gambit-like position with a huge development advantage} Re8+ 9. Nge2 a6 $36)
7... Ne8 8. f4 (8. cxb5 a6 $1 $146 {Continuing the Benko style! Strangely
enough, this move has not been played before} 9. bxa6 exd5 10. Qxd5 Nc7 11. Qd1
Re8 12. f4 Nc6 $36 {[%cal Yd7d5,Yd5d4] all Black's forces are well-placed} 13.
Nf3 d5 14. Kf2 c4 {[%csl Ya6] Black's advantage is out of doubt}) 8... exd5 9.
cxd5 d6 10. Nf3 {more or less a forced sequence until this moment} c4 11. a4 {
Other moves may lead to problems for White:} (11. Bd2 Nc7 12. a4 (12. Ne4 $2 {
underestimates Black's counterplay} Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2 dxe5 14. d6 {Despite the
beautiful pawn on d6, White is unable to parry all the threats on his center
since Black is better developed} Ne6 15. fxe5 Bb7 16. Ng3 Nd7 $17) 12... Bg4
$146 {Still offering the b5 pawn. However, Black gets tremendous activity
which more than compensates for the sacrifice} (12... Bb7 $2 13. axb5 $16 {
0-1 (61) Aditya,M (2680) -Nakamura, H (3167) Chess. com INT 2020}) 13. axb5 Nd7
14. Bxc4 (14. Be2 dxe5 $13) 14... Nxe5 $1 {[%csl Yc4,Ye1,Yh4] Exploiting the
hidden Qh4 motive:} 15. fxe5 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Qh4+ 17. Kd1 $1 {The only way to
keep the balance but a rather hard one to find} Qxc4 18. Qe4 Qb3+ 19. Qc2 Qc4
$11) (11. Be2 $6 {does not pose any problems to Black} Bb7 12. O-O Nc7 $36 {
[%csl Gd5] 0-1 (44) Tabernig,B (2327)-Bosiocic, M (2552) Trieste 2015}) 11...
Nd7 (11... Bg4 {has been previously played at the highest level too} 12. axb5
Nd7 13. e6 fxe6 14. dxe6 $36 {1-0 (38) Shirov,A (2749)-Kramnik,V (2780)
Shanghai 2010}) 12. Be2 (12. axb5 {Accepting the pawn leads to a sharp
double-edged battle. A sample line of how the play might continue:} dxe5 13.
Bxc4 Nd6 14. Be2 Qb6 $13 15. fxe5 (15. Bd2 {1/2-1/2 (23) Piesik,P (2403)-Kozak,
A (2503) Slovakia 2020} e4 16. Ne5 e3 17. Bc1 Nxb5 $36) 15... Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Re8
17. Nd3 Ne4 18. Qc2 Nxc3 19. bxc3 Bg4 20. Nxb4 Bxe2 21. Qxe2 Rxe2+ 22. Kxe2
Qxb5+ 23. Kd1 a5 24. Bd2 h6 25. Re1 Kh7 26. Nc2 Qxd5 27. Re2 a4 {1/2-1/2 (27)
Babic,D (2481)-Terreaux,G (2467) ICCF email 2017}) 12... Qb6 {Still following
mainstream theory} 13. Bd2 Nc7 14. Nxb5 Bxd2+ (14... Nxd5 {has been tested in
correspondence chess but the complications that ensue looked too impractical
to me} 15. Bxb4 Nxb4 16. Nxd6 Ba6 $13) 15. Qxd2 Nxb5 16. axb5 Re8 17. Qd4 {
A precise move that White needs to know to stay in the game} (17. e6 $6 fxe6
18. dxe6 Nc5 {with the pawn will drop soon}) 17... dxe5 18. fxe5 Bb7 {Not
rushing to capture on b5 and simplify} 19. e6 fxe6 20. Qxb6 Nxb6 {with a
balanced endgame 1/2-1/2 (20) Oreopoulos,K (2490)-Percze,J (2508) ICCF email
2019} *

