{[%evp 0,42,20,20,37,-3,6,6,23,-41,-25,-14,-17,-14,3,9,-15,1,7,10,10,21,33,10,
36,3,4,9,12,24,14,10,23,21,22,-6,-6,2,0,0,3,-22,-22,-46,-20]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 {This is what I suggest in my book. I like this choice
because after 4...0-0 5.e4!? there are long lines, where Black has to play
very precisely in order to equalize, and even then White is very safe.} 5. a3
Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 b6 $5 {A relatively rare idea. By delaying castling Black
manages to avoid lots of theoretical lines.} 7. Bg5 (7. Nf3 Ba6 8. e3 (8. cxd5
Ne4 $1 {An important intemrediate move. The same approach is effective in the
main lines with 6...0-0, like I mention in the book.} ({The immediate} 8...
exd5 9. Bg5 O-O 10. Rc1 {puts Black under pressure on the c-file.}) 9. Qc2 exd5
10. g3 O-O 11. Bg2 c5 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. O-O Nc6 $1 $146 {The most natural way
of development.} ({Much worse is} 13... Nd7 $2 14. Rd1 Ndf6 15. Ng5 $1 $16 {
The pawns centre was dicey in Kharlov,A (2593)-Nisipeanu, L (2692) Tripoli 2004
}) 14. b4 (14. Rd1 Rc8) 14... Qf6 15. Bb2 Nd4 16. Nxd4 cxd4 {[%csl Gd4,Gd5,Ge4]
The activity of pices fully compensates for some structural drawbacks. In
particular, Ne4-c3 is a powerful idea.} 17. Rad1 Rac8 {[%cal Ge4c3]}) 8... O-O
9. b4 c5 10. dxc5 bxc5 11. b5 (11. Bb2 Nbd7 12. cxd5 Bxf1 13. Kxf1 cxb4 14.
axb4 Rc8 15. Qd4 e5 $1 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Qxe5 Rc2 $40) 11... Bb7 12. Bb2 Nbd7
13. Be2 e5 $1 14. Nxe5 {0-1 (29) Vera Gonzalez Quevedo, R (2494)-Barlov,D  
(2439) La Laguna 2007} Nxe5 15. Qxe5 Re8) (7. cxd5 Ne4 $1 {Again, this
important intermediate move allows Black to avoid the nasty pin.} (7... exd5 8.
Bg5 $14) 8. Qc2 exd5 9. Bf4 ({After} 9. Nf3 O-O 10. g3 ({Riskier is} 10. Bf4 c5
11. dxc5 bxc5 12. e3 Bf5 13. Bd3 c4 $1 {Black takes full control over the
light squares, and it looks bad for White.}) 10... c5 11. dxc5 bxc5 12. Bg2 Ba6
{there is a transposition. Cf7}) ({Of course, not} 9. f3 $2 Qh4+ $19) 9... c5
10. f3 ({I've also examined} 10. e3 $146 cxd4 11. f3 ({After} 11. exd4 O-O 12.
Bd3 Qh4 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6]} 13. Bxe4 Re8 14. Ne2 dxe4 15. O-O Nd7 {the arising
middlegame position seems acceptable for Black due to control over the light
squares. True, the d-passer looks strong, but it is blocked for now.}) ({
The attempt to make the isolated pawn with} 11. Qa4+ Nd7 12. Qxd4 O-O {leaves
White too undeveloped, and it is illustrated in the following line:} 13. Qxd5
Bb7 $1 14. Qxb7 $2 Ndc5 {[%cal Gd8d2] with a collapse.}) 11... Nc5 12. exd4 Ne6
13. Be3 O-O {White temporarily has the bishops pair, but ...Ba6 is to follow
soon.} 14. Bd3 h6 15. Ne2 Ba6 16. Bxa6 ({Or} 16. O-O Bxd3 17. Qxd3 Nc6 $11)
16... Nxa6 17. O-O Qd7 $11) 10... Ng5 11. dxc5 Ne6 12. Bxb8 Rxb8 13. c6 ({
Bad is} 13. Qa4+ $2 {L'Ami,E (2610)-Timman,J (2562) London 2008} b5 $1 14. Qc2
O-O 15. e3 Re8 $36 {White struggles to complete development, while the extra
pawn has not much value in the middlegame.}) 13... b5 $1 {[%cal Gd8b6] Making
b6 vacant for the queen.} 14. Rc1 Qb6 15. Qd2 O-O $44 {Black has excellent
compensation for a pawn: the Ke1 is stuck in the centre, and most of his
pieces are on the initial spots.}) (7. e3 Ba6 8. Nf3 {is the same as 8.Nf3})
7... dxc4 8. e3 (8. e4 $2 Nxe4) (8. Qxc4 Ba6 9. Bxf6 ({Toothless is} 9. Qa4+
Qd7 10. Qxd7+ Nbxd7 11. Nf3 c5 {with an equal endgame.}) (9. Qc3 Nbd7 10. e3
Bxf1 11. Kxf1 Rc8 12. Qc6 O-O 13. Nf3 Nb8 14. Qb7 c5 {Black took over the
initiative in Papadakis,M (2102)-Andonovski,L (2300) Sunny Beach 2008}) 9...
Qxf6 10. Qa4+ c6 11. Nf3 O-O 12. e3 (12. Rc1 c5 13. e3 Bb7 $5 (13... Bxf1 {
is also possible.}) 14. Be2 Bc6 15. Qc2 {1-0 (35) Bernadskiy,V (2606)-Arnaudov,
P (2471) Belgrade 2021} cxd4 $146 16. exd4 Bd5 17. Qc7 Qd8 18. O-O Qxc7 19.
Rxc7 Nc6 20. Rc1 Rac8 21. Rxc8 Rxc8 22. Ne5 Ne7) 12... Bxf1 13. Kxf1 c5 14. Ke2
Rd8 15. Rhd1 Nd7 $11 {Luch - Stefansson, 2008}) 8... Bb7 9. Qxc4 Nbd7 10. Nf3
c5 11. Be2 h6 12. Bh4 O-O 13. O-O g5 14. Bg3 Ne4 15. Rfd1 {This was Mamedyarov,
S (2767)-Aronian,L (2758) Batumi 2019 My natural new idea here is} Qe7 {
connecting the rooks and making d8 vacant for one of them} 16. Rac1 Rfd8 17.
dxc5 Ndxc5 {Black will soon exchange the Bg3 and reach a full equlity. The
only attempt to deviate from it is} 18. Be5 ({risky is} 18. Ne5 Rd5 $1 {
, and then} 19. Rxd5 $2 exd5 {drops a piece.}) {, but then after} 18... g4 19.
Nd4 Rac8 20. Qb4 Qg5 21. Bf4 Qf6 {[%cal Ge6e5] Black takes over the initiative.
} *

