{[%evp 0,40,22,30,30,-3,-3,-2,26,28,22,22,22,6,-3,-12,8,8,19,17,21,1,5,9,-2,8,
3,20,24,13,13,16,13,23,10,14,20,15,21,14,14,20,37]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 {In this posiiton White has few options, but the most
challennig IMO are 6.Nf3 & 6.a3} 6. a3 (6. Nf3 dxc4 7. Bxc4 c5 8. O-O Nc6 9. a3
Ba5 10. Qd3 (10. Bd3 cxd4 11. exd4 h6 {[%cal Gc1g5]} 12. Be3 (12. Bc2 Bc7 $1 {
[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] A decent manoevre. The Ba5 did its job, and now Black is
relocating it to restrict the Bc1 and prepare fianchetto.} 13. Re1 (13. Qd3 e5
$1 {This is another idea behing Bc7} 14. dxe5 Qxd3 15. Bxd3 Nxe5 {is a
comfortable equality.}) (13. Be3 Ne7 14. Ne5 Nf5 15. Qd2 b6 16. Rad1 Bb7 17.
Bf4 Nd5 {Black had a good position in Caruana,F (2835)-Dominguez Perez,L (2758)
Lichess.org INT 2020}) 13... Re8 $5 {[%cal Ge6e5]} (13... b6 14. Qd3 Ne7 15.
Ne4 (15. Ne5 {0-1 (67) Danielian,E (2385)-Bluebaum,M (2643) Douglas 2019} Nf5
$1 $146 (15... Bb7 16. Qg3 {offers White some initiative.}) 16. Be3 (16. d5
Bxe5 $1 (16... Nxd5 17. Nc6 Qd6 18. Nxd5 Qxh2+ 19. Kf1) 17. Rxe5 Ng4 18. Re2
Nf6 19. dxe6 Bxe6 $11) 16... Bb7 17. Rad1 Bxe5 18. dxe5 Qxd3 19. Bxd3 Nxe3 20.
Rxe3 Nd5 $11) 15... Nf5 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6) 14. Be3 e5 15. Nb5 exd4 16. Nfxd4 Be5
$11) 12... Ne7 $5 $146 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gd7c6] This is my new idea. The knight
goes on f5 in order to cover the diagonal b1-h7 and put pressure on the
isolated pawn.} 13. Ne5 (13. Qe2 Nf5 14. Rad1 Bd7 15. Ne5 Rc8 $132) 13... Nf5
14. Rc1 Bb6 {By making this move Black practically forces White to exchange
the Nf5} 15. Bxf5 exf5) (10. Ne2 cxd4 11. Nexd4 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 e5 13. Nf3 Qc7
$11) 10... a6 $5 {Claiming the drawbacks of Qd3 - b7-b5 and c5-c4 is to follow.
